{"title_page": "Tutbury", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\t\n|static_image_name = Tutbury - Ye Olde Dog & Partridge.jpg\n|static_image_caption = The Dog & Partridge\n|official_name = Tutbury\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.854|-1.686|display=inline,title}}\n|population = 3076\n|population_ref = [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]]\n|shire_district = [[East Staffordshire]]\n|shire_county = [[Staffordshire]]\n|region = West Midlands\n|constituency_westminster = [[Burton (UK Parliament constituency)|Burton]]\n|post_town = BURTON-ON-TRENT\n|postcode_district = DE13\n|postcode_area = DE\n|dial_code = 01283\n|os_grid_reference = SK211285\n}}\n'''Tutbury''' is a large village and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] of about 3,076 residents in the [[England|English]] county of [[Staffordshire]].\n\nBIG ZOOTS GET BUN UP IN TUTBURY, TT FLAVOURS ABOUT EVERYWHERE, SMELL THAT GELATO FROM A MILE A WAY... TutVegas 4 lyf\n\nIt is surrounded by the agricultural countryside of both Staffordshire and [[Derbyshire]]. The site has been inhabited for over 3,000 years, with Iron Age defensive ditches encircling the main defensive hill, upon which now stand ruins of a Norman castle. These ditches can be seen most clearly at the Park pale and at the top of the steep hills behind Park Lane.\n\nThe name Tutbury probably derives from a [[Scandinavia]]n settler and subsequent chief of the hill-fort, Totta, ''bury'' being a corruption of ''burh'' the Anglo-Saxon name for 'fortified place'.\nIt is {{convert|5|mi}} north of [[Burton upon Trent]] and {{convert|20|mi}} south of the [[Peak District]].\n\nQuarries near Tutbury once produced [[alabaster]] which was used in the carving of [[Nottingham alabaster|Nottingham Alabaster]].\n\nUntil 2006, Tutbury Crystal, a manufacturer of high-quality cut glass products, was based in the village. However production was transferred to [[Stoke-on-Trent]] as the existing factory was very old and was thought to be too small for the modern company's requirements. The old factory was demolished and flats were built on the site, but a factory shop still operates in the village. Despite this, the tourism trade survives thanks to the long and distinguished history of the [[St Mary's Church, Tutbury|Norman Priory Church]] and medieval [[Tutbury Castle]] where [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], was once imprisoned.\n\n[[File:Tutbury castle.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Tutbury Castle at dusk]]\n[[File:West front of Tutbury Parish Church - geograph.org.uk - 1046109.jpg|thumb|right|175px|West front of St Mary's Church (circa 1160)]]\nThe castle became the headquarters of [[Henry de Ferrers]] and was the centre of the [[wapentake]] of Appletree, which included [[Duffield Frith]]. With his wife Bertha, he endowed Tutbury Priory with two manors in about 1080. It would seem that Tutbury at that time was a dependency of the [[Normans|Norman]] abbey of St Pierre\u2011sur\u2011Dives.<ref>Marios Costambeys, 'Ferrers, Henry de (d. 1093x1 100)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, Sept 2004; online edn, May 2007 [ 61, accessed 28 Oct 2007]</ref> One of the Royal Studs was established in the area round the castle by [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] but had to be abandoned after the [[English Civil War|Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tbheritage.com/Breeders/FoundBreeders/EarlyNotes.html| title= Some Notes on Foundation Breeders and Early Running Horses| publisher= Thoroughbred Heritage|accessdate= 2011-10-06}}</ref>\n\nUntil the 18th century, Tutbury was the site of an annual court of [[minstrel]]s.<ref>{{Cite book | title = History of the Castle, Priory and Town of Tutbury, in the county of Stafford\n| first = Oswald, Sir\n| last = Mosley\n| authorlink = Sir Oswald Mosley, 2nd Baronet, of Ancoats\n}}</ref> There was even a \"King of the Minstrels\".\n\nThere are some fine [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] and [[Regency era|Regency]] buildings and the half-timbered Dog and Partridge Hotel. There are antique and craft shops in the village some of which have been run by the same families for many years.\n\n[[Tutbury and Hatton railway station]], was opened by the [[North Staffordshire Railway]] on 11 September 1848. It then closed during the 1960s to reopen in 1989. It is on the [[Crewe to Derby Line]].\n\nTutbury Priory Church, dedicated to the [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Blessed Virgin Mary]], has a unique west door with the only known [[alabaster]] arch (circa 1160) in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tutburystmarys.org/priory-projects/copaa |title=CoPAA \u2013 Conservation of the Priory Alabaster Arch |publisher=St. Mary's Priory Church, Tutbury |accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\n\n''The Natural History of Tutbury'' describing the fauna and flora of the district surrounding Tutbury and Burton on Trent, by [[Sir Oswald Mosley, 2nd Baronet, of Ancoats|Sir Oswald Mosley]] and Edwin Brown, was published in 1863.<ref name=\"Mosley\">{{cite book|last1=Mosley|first1=Oswald|last2=Brown|first2=Edwin|title=The Natural History of Tutbury|year=1863}}</ref>\n\nThe village of Tutbury was featured in the [[Most Haunted]] spin-off series [[Most Haunted: Midsummer Murders]] where the team investigated a murder over hidden treasure.\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[William de Ferrers, 3rd Earl of Derby]] (died 1190) was an English Earl who resided in [[Tutbury Castle]]\n* [[Robert de Ferrers, 6th Earl of Derby]] (1239\u20131279) was an English nobleman, born at [[Tutbury Castle]]\n* [[Ann Moore (impostor)|Ann Moore]] (1761\u20131813) the notorious ''fasting-woman of Tutbury''. From 1807 to 1813, she claimed to have eaten nothing at all, but her claims were eventually shown to be a hoax. \n* [[Benjamin Brook]] (1776\u20131848) an English nonconformist minister and religious historian,  the first pastor of the congregational church at Tutbury in 1801\n* [[Walter Lyon (cricketer)|Walter Lyon]] (1841\u20131918 in Tutbury) an English cricketer who played in first-class cricket matches for Cambridge University between 1861 and 1863. In 1865, he and his younger brother Charles moved to Tutbury to take over the cotton mill \n* [[John Henry Davies]] (c. 1864 in Tutbury \u2013 1927) a wealthy British brewery owner who in 1902 took over the football club [[History of Manchester United F.C. (1878\u20131945)|Manchester United]], which was then called Newton Heath.\n* [[Thomas Richardson (cricketer)|Thomas Richardson]] (1865\u20131923) cricketer who played first-class cricket for Derbyshire in 1895. Born and died in Tutbury\n* [[George Harris (footballer, born 1877)|George Harris]] (born 1877) an English professional footballer who played 71 pro games and on retirement became the landlord of a public house at Tutbury\n* Air Vice Marshal [[William Staton]], CB, DSO & Bar, MC, DFC & Bar (1898 in Tutbury \u2013 1983) a WW1 British airman, later WW2 Japanese [[Prisoner of war|PoW]] and senior RAF officer\n* [[Joseph Nelis]] (1917\u20131994) a Belgian footballer, was born in Tutbury\n\n==See also==\n*[[Listed buildings in Tutbury]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tutbury}}\n*[http://www.upmystreet.com/overview/?l1=tutbury Information from UpMyStreet]\n*{{mmukscaled|SK211291|25|Map from MultiMap}}\n*[http://www.streetmap.co.uk/newmap.srf?x=420500&y=328500&z=1&sv=420500,328500&st=4&mapp=newmap.srf&searchp=newsearch.srf Map from StreetMap]\n*[http://www.burton-on-trent.net/?CategoryID=8 Tutbury Community Forum]\n*[http://www.hauntedhappenings.co.uk/tutburycastle/ghosts-of-tutbury-castle.php Hauntings of Tutbury]\n*[https://loveburton.uk/category/tutbury/ Love Burton Tutbury Page]\n{{Civil Parishes of East Stafford}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Borough of East Staffordshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\t\n|static_image_name = Tutbury - Ye Olde Dog & Partridge.jpg\n|static_image_caption = The Dog & Partridge\n|official_name = Tutbury\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.854|-1.686|display=inline,title}}\n|population = 3076\n|population_ref = [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]]\n|shire_district = [[East Staffordshire]]\n|shire_county = [[Staffordshire]]\n|region = West Midlands\n|constituency_westminster = [[Burton (UK Parliament constituency)|Burton]]\n|post_town = BURTON-ON-TRENT\n|postcode_district = DE13\n|postcode_area = DE\n|dial_code = 01283\n|os_grid_reference = SK211285\n}}\n'''Tutbury''' is a large village and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] of about 3,076 residents in the [[England|English]] county of [[Staffordshire]].\n\nIt is surrounded by the agricultural countryside of both Staffordshire and [[Derbyshire]]. The site has been inhabited for over 3,000 years, with Iron Age defensive ditches encircling the main defensive hill, upon which now stand ruins of a Norman castle. These ditches can be seen most clearly at the Park pale and at the top of the steep hills behind Park Lane.\n\nThe name Tutbury probably derives from a [[Scandinavia]]n settler and subsequent chief of the hill-fort, Totta, ''bury'' being a corruption of ''burh'' the Anglo-Saxon name for 'fortified place'.\nIt is {{convert|5|mi}} north of [[Burton upon Trent]] and {{convert|20|mi}} south of the [[Peak District]].\n\nQuarries near Tutbury once produced [[alabaster]] which was used in the carving of [[Nottingham alabaster|Nottingham Alabaster]].\n\nUntil 2006, Tutbury Crystal, a manufacturer of high-quality cut glass products, was based in the village. However production was transferred to [[Stoke-on-Trent]] as the existing factory was very old and was thought to be too small for the modern company's requirements. The old factory was demolished and flats were built on the site, but a factory shop still operates in the village. Despite this, the tourism trade survives thanks to the long and distinguished history of the [[St Mary's Church, Tutbury|Norman Priory Church]] and medieval [[Tutbury Castle]] where [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], was once imprisoned.\n\n[[File:Tutbury castle.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Tutbury Castle at dusk]]\n[[File:West front of Tutbury Parish Church - geograph.org.uk - 1046109.jpg|thumb|right|175px|West front of St Mary's Church (circa 1160)]]\nThe castle became the headquarters of [[Henry de Ferrers]] and was the centre of the [[wapentake]] of Appletree, which included [[Duffield Frith]]. With his wife Bertha, he endowed Tutbury Priory with two manors in about 1080. It would seem that Tutbury at that time was a dependency of the [[Normans|Norman]] abbey of St Pierre\u2011sur\u2011Dives.<ref>Marios Costambeys, 'Ferrers, Henry de (d. 1093x1 100)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, Sept 2004; online edn, May 2007 [ 61, accessed 28 Oct 2007]</ref> One of the Royal Studs was established in the area round the castle by [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] but had to be abandoned after the [[English Civil War|Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tbheritage.com/Breeders/FoundBreeders/EarlyNotes.html| title= Some Notes on Foundation Breeders and Early Running Horses| publisher= Thoroughbred Heritage|accessdate= 2011-10-06}}</ref>\n\nUntil the 18th century, Tutbury was the site of an annual court of [[minstrel]]s.<ref>{{Cite book | title = History of the Castle, Priory and Town of Tutbury, in the county of Stafford\n| first = Oswald, Sir\n| last = Mosley\n| authorlink = Sir Oswald Mosley, 2nd Baronet, of Ancoats\n}}</ref> There was even a \"King of the Minstrels\".\n\nThere are some fine [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] and [[Regency era|Regency]] buildings and the half-timbered Dog and Partridge Hotel. There are antique and craft shops in the village some of which have been run by the same families for many years.\n\n[[Tutbury and Hatton railway station]], was opened by the [[North Staffordshire Railway]] on 11 September 1848. It then closed during the 1960s to reopen in 1989. It is on the [[Crewe to Derby Line]].\n\nTutbury Priory Church, dedicated to the [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Blessed Virgin Mary]], has a unique west door with the only known [[alabaster]] arch (circa 1160) in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tutburystmarys.org/priory-projects/copaa |title=CoPAA \u2013 Conservation of the Priory Alabaster Arch |publisher=St. Mary's Priory Church, Tutbury |accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\n\n''The Natural History of Tutbury'' describing the fauna and flora of the district surrounding Tutbury and Burton on Trent, by [[Sir Oswald Mosley, 2nd Baronet, of Ancoats|Sir Oswald Mosley]] and Edwin Brown, was published in 1863.<ref name=\"Mosley\">{{cite book|last1=Mosley|first1=Oswald|last2=Brown|first2=Edwin|title=The Natural History of Tutbury|year=1863}}</ref>\n\nThe village of Tutbury was featured in the [[Most Haunted]] spin-off series [[Most Haunted: Midsummer Murders]] where the team investigated a murder over hidden treasure.\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[William de Ferrers, 3rd Earl of Derby]] (died 1190) was an English Earl who resided in [[Tutbury Castle]]\n* [[Robert de Ferrers, 6th Earl of Derby]] (1239\u20131279) was an English nobleman, born at [[Tutbury Castle]]\n* [[Ann Moore (impostor)|Ann Moore]] (1761\u20131813) the notorious ''fasting-woman of Tutbury''. From 1807 to 1813, she claimed to have eaten nothing at all, but her claims were eventually shown to be a hoax. \n* [[Benjamin Brook]] (1776\u20131848) an English nonconformist minister and religious historian,  the first pastor of the congregational church at Tutbury in 1801\n* [[Walter Lyon (cricketer)|Walter Lyon]] (1841\u20131918 in Tutbury) an English cricketer who played in first-class cricket matches for Cambridge University between 1861 and 1863. In 1865, he and his younger brother Charles moved to Tutbury to take over the cotton mill \n* [[John Henry Davies]] (c. 1864 in Tutbury \u2013 1927) a wealthy British brewery owner who in 1902 took over the football club [[History of Manchester United F.C. (1878\u20131945)|Manchester United]], which was then called Newton Heath.\n* [[Thomas Richardson (cricketer)|Thomas Richardson]] (1865\u20131923) cricketer who played first-class cricket for Derbyshire in 1895. Born and died in Tutbury\n* [[George Harris (footballer, born 1877)|George Harris]] (born 1877) an English professional footballer who played 71 pro games and on retirement became the landlord of a public house at Tutbury\n* Air Vice Marshal [[William Staton]], CB, DSO & Bar, MC, DFC & Bar (1898 in Tutbury \u2013 1983) a WW1 British airman, later WW2 Japanese [[Prisoner of war|PoW]] and senior RAF officer\n* [[Joseph Nelis]] (1917\u20131994) a Belgian footballer, was born in Tutbury\n\n==See also==\n*[[Listed buildings in Tutbury]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tutbury}}\n*[http://www.upmystreet.com/overview/?l1=tutbury Information from UpMyStreet]\n*{{mmukscaled|SK211291|25|Map from MultiMap}}\n*[http://www.streetmap.co.uk/newmap.srf?x=420500&y=328500&z=1&sv=420500,328500&st=4&mapp=newmap.srf&searchp=newsearch.srf Map from StreetMap]\n*[http://www.burton-on-trent.net/?CategoryID=8 Tutbury Community Forum]\n*[http://www.hauntedhappenings.co.uk/tutburycastle/ghosts-of-tutbury-castle.php Hauntings of Tutbury]\n*[https://loveburton.uk/category/tutbury/ Love Burton Tutbury Page]\n{{Civil Parishes of East Stafford}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Borough of East Staffordshire]]\n", "name_user": "95.150.90.169", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tutbury"}
{"title_page": "Moral foundations theory", "text_new": "'''Moral foundations theory''' is a [[social psychological]] theory intended to explain the origins of and variation in human moral reasoning on the basis of innate, modular foundations.<ref name=\"Haidt2004\">{{cite journal|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|author2=Craig Joseph|title=Intuitive ethics: how innately prepared intuitions generate culturally variable virtues|journal=Daedalus|date=Fall 2004|volume=133|issue=4|pages=55\u201366|url=http://faculty.virginia.edu/haidtlab/articles/haidt.joseph.2004.intuitive-ethics.pub035.pdf|doi=10.1162/0011526042365555}} {{Dead link |date=March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Graham2013\">{{cite book | last1=Graham | first1=J. | last2=Haidt | first2=J.| last3=Koleva | first3=S.| last4=Motyl | first4=M.| last5=Iyer | first5=R.| last6=Wojcik | first6=S.| last7=Ditto | first7=P.H.| title=Moral Foundations Theory: The pragmatic validity of moral pluralism | journal=Advances in Experimental Social Psychology | volume=47 | year=2013 | pages=55\u2013130 | url=http://www-bcf.usc.edu/~jessegra/papers/GHKMIWD.inpress.MFT.AESP.pdf | doi=10.1016/b978-0-12-407236-7.00002-4| isbn=9780124072367 }} {{Dead link |date=March 2020}}</ref> It was first proposed by the psychologists [[Jonathan Haidt]], Craig Joseph and Jesse Graham, building on the work of cultural anthropologist [[Richard Shweder]];<ref name=\"Shweder1997\">{{cite book |last1=Shweder |first1=Richard |last2=Much |first2=Nancy |last3=Mahapatra |first3=Manamohan |last4=Park |first4=Lawrence |editor1-last=Brandt |editor1-first=Allan |editor2-last=Rozin |editor2-first=Paul |title=Morality and Health |publisher=Routledge |pages=119\u2013169 |date=1997 |chapter=The \"big three\" of morality (autonomy, community, divinity) and the \"big three\" explanations of suffering.}}</ref> and subsequently developed by a diverse group of collaborators, and popularized in Haidt's book ''[[The Righteous Mind]]''.<ref name=Haidt>{{cite book|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|title=The Righteous Mind: Why Good People are Divided By Politics and Religion|year=2012|publisher=Pantheon Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0-307-37790-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/righteousmindwhy0000haid/page/9 9\u201311]|url=https://archive.org/details/righteousmindwhy0000haid/page/9}}</ref> The theory proposes six foundations: Care/Harm, Fairness/Cheating, Loyalty/Betrayal, Authority/Subversion, Sanctity/Degradation, and Liberty/Oppression;<ref name=\"Iyer2012\">{{cite journal|journal= PLOS One|last1=Iyer|first1=Ravi|first2=Spassena|last2= Koleva|first3=Jesse |last3= Graham|first4=Peter |last4= Ditto|first5=Jonathan|last5= Haidt |title= Understanding Libertarian Morality: The Psychological Dispositions of Self-Identified Libertarians|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0042366|pmid= 22927928 |pmc= 3424229|volume= 7 |issue = 8|year=2012 |page= e42366 |bibcode=2012PLoSO...742366I}}</ref><ref name=Haidt /> while its authors remain open to the addition, subtraction or modification of the set of foundations.<ref name=\"Graham2013\"/>{{rp|pages=104\u2013107}}\n\nAlthough the initial development of moral foundations theory focused on cultural differences, subsequent work with the theory has largely focused on political ideology. Various scholars have offered moral foundations theory as an explanation of differences among political [[progressives]] ([[Liberalism|liberals]] in the American sense), [[conservatives]], and [[libertarians]], and have suggested that it can explain variation in opinion on politically charged issues such as same sex marriage and abortion.<ref name=\"Koleva2012\">{{cite journal |last1=Koleva |first1=Spassena P. |last2=Graham |first2=Jesse |last3=Iyer |first3=Ravi |last4=Ditto |first4=Peter H. |last5=Haidt |first5=Jonathan |title=Tracing the threads: How five moral concerns (especially Purity) help explain culture war attitudes |journal=Journal of Research in Personality |date=April 2012 |volume=46 |issue=2 |pages=184\u2013194 |doi=10.1016/j.jrp.2012.01.006}}</ref>\n\nThe two main sources are ''The Pragmatic Validity of Moral Pluralism''<ref name=\"Graham2013\" /> and ''Mapping the Moral Domain''.<ref name=\"Graham2011\">{{cite journal |last1=Graham |first1=Jesse |last2=Nosek |first2=Brian A. |last3=Haidt |first3=Jonathan |last4=Iyer |first4=Ravi |last5=Koleva |first5=Spassena |last6=Ditto |first6=Peter H. |title=Mapping the moral domain. |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |date=2011 |volume=101 |issue=2 |pages=366\u2013385 |doi=10.1037/a0021847 |pmid=21244182 |pmc=3116962 |url=http://www-bcf.usc.edu/~jessegra/papers/GNHIKD.2011.Mapping%20the%20moral%20domain.JPSP.pdf}} {{Dead link |date=March 2020}}</ref> In the first Haidt and Graham describe their work as looking, as anthropologists, at the evolution of morality and finding the common ground between each variation. In the second they describe and defend their method, known as the Moral Foundations Questionnaire. Through various trials and a participation population that consisted of over 11,000 people, from all ages and political beliefs, they were able to find results that supported their prediction.\n\n==Origins==\nMoral foundations theory was first proposed in 2004 by Haidt and Joseph.<ref name=\"Haidt2004\" /> The theory emerged as a reaction against the developmental rationalist theory of morality associated with [[Lawrence Kohlberg]] and [[Jean Piaget]].<ref name=\"Haidt2001\">{{cite journal|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|title=The Emotional Dog and Its Rational Tail: A Social Intuitionist Approach to Moral Judgement|journal=Psychological Review|date=October 2001|volume=108|issue=4|pages=814\u201334|url=http://www.nd.edu/~wcarbona/Haidt%202001.pdf|doi=10.1037/0033-295x.108.4.814|pmid=11699120|citeseerx=10.1.1.620.5536}} {{Dead link |date=March 2020}}</ref> Building on Piaget's work, Kohlberg argued that children's moral reasoning changed over time, and proposed an explanation through his six [[Kohlberg's stages of moral development|stages of moral development]]. Kohlberg's work emphasized justice as the key concept in moral reasoning, seen as a primarily cognitive activity, and became the dominant approach to moral psychology, heavily influencing subsequent work.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Donleavy|first=Gabriel|title=No Man's Land: Exploring the Space between Gilligan and Kohlberg|journal=Journal of Business Ethics|date=July 2008|volume=80|issue=4|pages=807\u2013822|jstor=25482183|doi=10.1007/s10551-007-9470-9}}</ref><ref name=Haidt /> Haidt writes that he found Kohlberg's theories unsatisfying from the time he first encountered them in graduate school because they \"seemed too cerebral\" and lacked a focus on issues of [[emotion]].\n\nIn contrast to the dominant theories of morality in psychology, the anthropologist Richard Shweder developed a set of theories emphasizing the cultural variability of moral judgments, but argued that different cultural forms of morality drew on \"three distinct but coherent clusters of moral concerns\", which he labeled as the ethics of autonomy, community, and divinity.<ref name=\"Shweder1997\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Shweder|first=Richard|author2=Jonathan Haidt|title=Commentary to Feature Review: The Future of Moral Psychology: Truth, Intuition, and the Pluralist Way|journal=Psychological Science|date=November 1993|volume=4|issue=6|pages=360\u2013365|jstor=40062563|doi=10.1111/j.1467-9280.1993.tb00582.x}}</ref> Shweder's approach inspired Haidt to begin researching moral differences across cultures, including fieldwork in Brazil and Philadelphia.<ref name=\"Haidt1993\">{{cite journal |last1=Haidt |first1=Jonathan |last2=Koller |first2=Silvia Helena |last3=Dias |first3=Maria G. |title=Affect, culture, and morality, or is it wrong to eat your dog? |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |date=1993 |volume=65 |issue=4 |pages=613\u2013628 |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.65.4.613|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/837091f3ac8cc6047833de330315e3f2c46b5af6 }}</ref> This work led Haidt to begin developing his [[Social intuitionism|social intuitionist]] approach to morality. This approach, which stood in sharp contrast to Kohlberg's rationalist work, suggested that \"moral judgment is caused by quick moral intuitions\" while moral reasoning simply serves as a post-hoc rationalization of already formed judgments.<ref name=\"Haidt2001\" /> Haidt's work and his focus on quick, intuitive, emotional judgments quickly became very influential, attracting sustained attention from an array of researchers.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Miller|first=Greg|title=The Roots of Morality|journal=Science|date=9 May 2008|volume=320|issue=5877|pages=734\u2013737|doi=10.1126/science.320.5877.734|pmid=18467565}}</ref>\n\nAs Haidt and his collaborators worked within the social intuitionist approach, they began to devote attention to the sources of the intuitions that they believed underlay moral judgments. In a 2004 article published in the journal [[Daedalus (journal)|Daedalus]],<ref name=\"Haidt2004\" /> Haidt and Joseph surveyed works on the roots of morality, including the work of [[Frans de Waal]], [[Donald Brown (anthropologist)|Donald Brown]] and Shweder, as well as [[Alan Fiske|Alan Fiske's]] [[Relational models theory|Relational Models Theory]] and [[Shalom Schwartz|Shalom Schwartz's]] [[Theory of Basic Human Values]]. From their review of these earlier lines of research, they suggested that all individuals possess four \"intuitive ethics\", stemming from the process of [[human evolution]] as responses to adaptive challenges. They labelled these four ethics as suffering, hierarchy, reciprocity, and purity.  According to Haidt and Joseph, each of the ethics formed a [[cognitive module]], whose development was shaped by culture.  They wrote that each module could \"provide little more than flashes of affect when certain patterns are encountered in the social world\", while a cultural learning process shaped each individual's response to these flashes. Morality diverges because different cultures utilize the four \"building blocks\" provided by the modules differently.<ref name=\"Haidt2004\" /> This article became the first statement of moral foundations theory, which Haidt, Joseph, and others have since elaborated and refined.\n\n==The five foundations==\nAccording to Moral Foundations Theory, differences in people's moral concerns can be described in terms of five moral foundations:\n* ''Care'': cherishing and protecting others; opposite of ''harm''\n* ''Fairness'' or ''proportionality'': rendering justice according to shared rules; opposite of ''cheating''\n* ''Loyalty'' or ''ingroup'': standing with your [[Ingroups_and_outgroups|group]], family, nation; opposite of ''betrayal''\n* ''Authority'' or ''respect'': submitting to tradition and legitimate authority; opposite of ''subversion''\n* ''Sanctity'' or ''purity'': abhorrence for disgusting things, foods, actions; opposite of ''degradation''\n\nThese five foundations are argued to group into two higher-order clusters \u2013 the person-focused ''Individualizing'' cluster of Care and Fairness, and the group-focused ''Binding'' cluster of Loyalty, Authority and Sanctity.<ref name= \"Graham2009\" /><ref name=\"Haidt&Graham2009\">{{cite book |last1=Haidt |first1=Jonathan |last2=Graham |first2=Jesse |editor1-last=Jost |editor1-first=John |editor2-last=Kay |editor2-first=Aaron |editor3-last=Thorisdottir |editor3-first=Hulda |title=Social and psychological bases of ideology and system justification |date=2009 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199869541 |pages=371\u2013401 |chapter=Planet of the Durkheimians, where community, authority, and sacredness are foundations of morality}}</ref> The empirical evidence favoring this grouping comes from patterns of associations between the moral foundations observed with the Moral Foundations Questionnaire.<ref name= \"Graham2009\" /><ref name= \"Graham2011\" />\n\nA sixth foundation, ''liberty'' (opposite of ''oppression'') was theorized by [[Jonathan Haidt]] in ''[[The Righteous Mind]]'',<ref name=Haidt /> chapter eight, in response to the need to differentiate between proportionality fairness and the objections he had received from conservatives and [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarians]] (United States usage) to coercion by a dominating power or person.<ref name=\"Iyer2012\" /> Haidt noted that the latter group's moral matrix relies almost entirely on the ''liberty'' foundation.\n\n==Methods==\nA large amount of research on Moral Foundations Theory uses self-report instruments such as the Moral Foundations Questionnaire,<ref name=\"Graham2011\" /> the Moral Foundations Sacredness Scale,<ref name=\"Graham2012\">{{cite book |last1=Graham |first1=Jesse |last2=Haidt |first2=Jonathan |editor1-last=Mikulincer |editor1-first=Mario |editor2-last=Shaver |editor2-first=Phillip R |title=The Social Psychology of Morality: Exploring the Causes of Good and Evil |date=2012 |publisher=APA Books |isbn=978-1433810114 |chapter=Sacred values and evil adversaries: A moral foundations approach}}</ref> and Moral Foundations Vignettes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Clifford |first1=Scott |last2=Iyengar |first2=Vijeth |last3=Cabeza |first3=Roberto |last4=Sinnott-Armstrong |first4=Walter |title=Moral foundations vignettes: a standardized stimulus database of scenarios based on moral foundations theory |journal=Behavior Research Methods |date=13 January 2015 |volume=47 |issue=4 |pages=1178\u20131198 |doi=10.3758/s13428-014-0551-2|pmid=25582811 |pmc=4780680 }}</ref> Research on moral language use have also relied on variants of a Moral Foundations Dictionary.<ref name=\"Graham2009\">{{cite journal |last1=Graham |first1=Jesse |last2=Haidt |first2=Jonathan |last3=Nosek |first3=Brian A. |title=Liberals and conservatives rely on different sets of moral foundations. |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |date=2009 |volume=96 |issue=5 |pages=1029\u20131046 |doi=10.1037/a0015141|pmid=19379034 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/36d3bc7659ef1dc4c8504b6a0cb82329b0ac39bf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hoover |first1=Joe |last2=Johnson |first2=Kate |last3=Boghrati |first3=Reihane |last4=Graham |first4=Jesse |last5=Dehghani |first5=Morteza |title=Moral Framing and Charitable Donation: Integrating Exploratory Social Media Analyses and Confirmatory Experimentation |journal=Collabra: Psychology |date=26 April 2018 |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=9 |doi=10.1525/collabra.129}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Matsuo |first1=Akiko |last2=Sasahara |first2=Kazutoshi |last3=Taguchi |first3=Yasuhiro |last4=Karasawa |first4=Minoru |last5=Gruebner |first5=Oliver |title=Development and validation of the Japanese Moral Foundations Dictionary |journal=PLOS One |date=25 March 2019 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=e0213343 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0213343|pmid=30908489 |pmc=6433225 |arxiv=1804.00871 }}</ref> Researchers have also examined the topographical maps of somatosensory reactions associated with violations of different moral foundations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Atari|first=Mohammad|last2=Mostafazadeh Davani|first2=Aida|last3=Dehghani|first3=Morteza|date=2020-01-08|title=Body Maps of Moral Concerns|journal=Psychological Science|volume=31|issue=2|language=en|pages=160\u2013169|doi=10.1177/0956797619895284|pmid=31913779|issn=0956-7976}}</ref> Specifically, in a study where participants were asked to describe key aspects of their subjective somatosensory experience in response to scenarios involving various moral violations, body patterns corresponding to violations of moral foundations were felt in different regions of the body depending on whether participants were liberal or conservative.\n\n==Applications==\n\n===Political ideology===\n[[File:MFQResultsExample2.jpg|thumb|Results of the Moral Foundations Questionnaire]]\nResearchers have found that people's sensitivities to the five/six moral foundations correlate with their political ideologies. Using the Moral Foundations Questionnaire, Haidt and Graham found that libertarians are most sensitive to the proposed Liberty foundation,<ref name=\"Haidt\" /> liberals are most sensitive to the Care and Fairness foundations, while conservatives are equally sensitive to all five/six foundations.<ref name=\"Graham2011\" />  [[Joshua Greene (psychologist)|Joshua Greene]] argued however that liberals tend to emphasise the Care, Fairness and Liberty dimensions; conservatives the Loyalty, Authority and Sanctity dimensions.<ref>R Sapolsky, ''Behave'' (London 2018) p. 450</ref>\n\nAccording to Haidt, the differences have significant implications for political discourse and relations. Because members of two political camps are to a degree blind to one or more of the moral foundations of the others, they may perceive morally driven words or behavior as having another basis\u2014at best self-interested, at worst evil, and thus demonize one another.<ref name=\"Moyers\">{{cite AV media\n | people = Jonathan Haidt, Bill Moyers\n | title = Jonathan Haidt Explains Our Contentious Culture\n | medium = Television production\n | publisher = Public Square Media, Inc.\n | location = Lebanon\n | date = 3 February 2012\n | url = http://billmoyers.com/segment/jonathan-haidt-explains-our-contentious-culture/}}</ref>\n\nHaidt and Graham suggest a compromise can be found to allow liberals and conservatives to see eye-to-eye.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|last2=Graham|first2=Jesse|date=2007-06-01|title=When Morality Opposes Justice: Conservatives Have Moral Intuitions that Liberals may not Recognize|journal=Social Justice Research|language=en|volume=20|issue=1|pages=98\u2013116|doi=10.1007/s11211-007-0034-z|issn=0885-7466}}</ref> They suggest that the five foundations can be used as \"doorway\" to allow liberals to step to the conservative side of the \"wall\" put up between these two political affiliations on major political issues (i.e. legalizing gay marriage). If liberals try to consider the latter three foundations in addition to the former two (therefore adopting all five foundations like conservatives for a brief amount of time) they could understand where the conservatives' viewpoints stem from and long-lasting political issues could finally be settled.\n\nResearchers postulate that the moral foundations arose as solutions to problems common in the [[Evolutionary psychology|ancestral hunter-gatherer environment]], in particular intertribal and intra-tribal conflict. The three foundations emphasized more by conservatives (Loyalty, Authority, Sanctity) bind groups together for greater strength in intertribal competition while the other two foundations balance those tendencies with concern for individuals within the group. With reduced sensitivity to the group moral foundations, progressives tend to promote a more [[universalist]] morality.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Sinn | first1 = J.S. | last2 = Hayes | first2 = M.W. | year = 2017 | title = Replacing the Moral Foundations: An Evolutionary\u2010Coalitional Theory of Liberal\u2010Conservative Differences | url = | journal = Political Psychology | volume = 38 | issue = 6| pages = 1043\u20131064 | doi=10.1111/pops.12361}}</ref>\n\n===Cross-cultural differences===\nHaidt's initial field work in Brazil and Philadelphia in 1989,<ref name=\"Haidt1993\" /> and [[Odisha]], India in 1993, showed that moralizing indeed varies among cultures, but less than by social class (e.g. education) and age. Working-class Brazilian children were more likely to consider both taboo violations and infliction of harm to be morally wrong, and universally so. Members of traditional, [[collectivist]] societies, like political conservatives, are more sensitive to violations of the community-related moral foundations. Adult members of so-called WEIRD (western, educated, industrialized, rich, and democratic) societies are the most [[individualistic]], and most likely to draw a distinction between harm-inflicting violations of morality and violations of convention.<ref name=\"Haidt\" />\n\nSubsequent investigations of moral foundations theory in other cultures have found broadly similar correlations between morality and political identification to those of the US, with studies taking place in Korea, Sweden and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Kim1\">{{cite journal|last=Kim|first=Kisok|author2=Je-Sang Kang|author3=Seongyi Yun|title=Moral intuitions and political orientation: Similarities and differences between Korea and the United States|journal=Psychological Reports|date=August 2012|volume=111|issue=1|pages=173\u2013185|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0050092|pmid=23251357|pmc=3520939}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nilsson |first1=Artur |last2=Erlandsson |first2=Arvid |title=The Moral Foundations taxonomy: Structural validity and relation to political ideology in Sweden |journal=Personality and Individual Differences |date=April 2015 |volume=76 |pages=28\u201332 |doi=10.1016/j.paid.2014.11.049}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Davies |first1=Caitlin L. |last2=Sibley |first2=Chris G. |last3=Liu |first3=James H. |title=Confirmatory Factor Analysis of the Moral Foundations Questionnaire |journal=Social Psychology |date=November 2014 |volume=45 |issue=6 |pages=431\u2013436 |doi=10.1027/1864-9335/a000201}}</ref>\n\n==Critiques and competing theories==\nA number of researchers have offered critiques of, and alternative theories to, Moral Foundations Theory. Critiques of the theory have included claims of biological implausibility<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Suhler |first1=Christopher L. |last2=Churchland |first2=Patricia |title=Can Innate, Modular \"Foundations\" Explain Morality? Challenges for Haidt's Moral Foundations Theory |journal=Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience |date=September 2011 |volume=23 |issue=9 |pages=2103\u20132116 |doi=10.1162/jocn.2011.21637|pmid=21291315 }}</ref> and redundancy among the moral foundations (which are argued to be reducible to concern about harm).<ref name=\"Schein2017\">{{cite journal |last1=Schein |first1=Chelsea |last2=Gray |first2=Kurt |title=The Theory of Dyadic Morality: Reinventing Moral Judgment by Redefining Harm |journal=Personality and Social Psychology Review |date=14 May 2017 |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=32\u201370 |doi=10.1177/1088868317698288|pmid=28504021 }}</ref> Both critiques have been disputed by the original authors.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Haidt |first1=Jonathan |last2=Joseph |first2=Craig |title=How Moral Foundations Theory Succeeded in Building on Sand: A Response to Suhler and Churchland |journal=Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience |date=September 2011 |volume=23 |issue=9 |pages=2117\u20132122 |doi=10.1162/jocn.2011.21638}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Koleva |first1=Spassena |last2=Haidt |first2=Jonathan |title=Let's Use Einstein's Safety Razor, Not Occam's Swiss Army Knife or Occam's Chainsaw |journal=Psychological Inquiry |date=April 2012 |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=175\u2013178 |doi=10.1080/1047840X.2012.667678}}</ref> Alternative theories include the Model of Moral Motives,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Janoff-Bulman |first1=Ronnie |last2=Carnes |first2=Nate C. |title=Surveying the Moral Landscape |journal=Personality and Social Psychology Review |date=16 March 2013 |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=219\u2013236 |doi=10.1177/1088868313480274|pmid=23504824 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f9a39f98565d26daeff64d205d8b450d1b0a94f4 }}</ref> the Theory of Dyadic Morality,<ref name=\"Gray2012\">{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Kurt |last2=Young |first2=Liane |last3=Waytz |first3=Adam |title=Mind Perception Is the Essence of Morality |journal=Psychological Inquiry |date=April 2012 |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=101\u2013124 |doi=10.1080/1047840X.2012.651387|pmid=22754268 |pmc=3379786 }}</ref><ref name=\"Schein2017\"/> Relationship Regulation Theory,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rai |first1=Tage Shakti |last2=Fiske |first2=Alan Page |title=Moral psychology is relationship regulation: Moral motives for unity, hierarchy, equality, and proportionality. |journal=Psychological Review |date=2011 |volume=118 |issue=1 |pages=57\u201375 |doi=10.1037/a0021867|pmid=21244187 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/30d6fd35f01cc6282b39928c5b3edfd4f836659a }}</ref> the [[right-wing authoritarianism]] scale developed by [[Bob Altemeyer]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Verhulst|first1=B.|last2=Eaves|first2=L. J.|last3=Hatemi|first3=P. K.|year=2012|title=Correlation not causation: the relationship between personality traits and political ideologies.|journal=American Journal of Political Science|volume=56|issue=1|pages=34\u201351|doi=10.1111/j.1540-5907.2011.00568.x|pmid=22400142|pmc=3809096}}</ref> and the theory of Morality As Cooperation.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Curry |first1=Oliver Scott |last2=Jones Chesters |first2=Matthew |last3=Van Lissa |first3=Caspar J. |title=Mapping morality with a compass: Testing the theory of 'morality-as-cooperation' with a new questionnaire |journal=Journal of Research in Personality |date=February 2019 |volume=78 |pages=106\u2013124 |doi=10.1016/j.jrp.2018.10.008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://moralfoundations.org/ moralfoundations.org]\n\n[[Category:Psychological theories]]\n[[Category:Psychology articles needing infoboxes]]\n[[Category:Evolutionary psychology]]\n[[Category:Moral psychology]]\n", "text_old": "'''Moral foundations theory''' is a [[social psychological]] theory intended to explain the origins of and variation in human moral reasoning on the basis of innate, modular foundations.<ref name=\"Haidt2004\">{{cite journal|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|author2=Craig Joseph|title=Intuitive ethics: how innately prepared intuitions generate culturally variable virtues|journal=Daedalus|date=Fall 2004|volume=133|issue=4|pages=55\u201366|url=http://faculty.virginia.edu/haidtlab/articles/haidt.joseph.2004.intuitive-ethics.pub035.pdf|doi=10.1162/0011526042365555}} {{Dead link |date=March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Graham2013\">{{cite book | last1=Graham | first1=J. | last2=Haidt | first2=J.| last3=Koleva | first3=S.| last4=Motyl | first4=M.| last5=Iyer | first5=R.| last6=Wojcik | first6=S.| last7=Ditto | first7=P.H.| title=Moral Foundations Theory: The pragmatic validity of moral pluralism | journal=Advances in Experimental Social Psychology | volume=47 | year=2013 | pages=55\u2013130 | url=http://www-bcf.usc.edu/~jessegra/papers/GHKMIWD.inpress.MFT.AESP.pdf | doi=10.1016/b978-0-12-407236-7.00002-4| isbn=9780124072367 }} {{Dead link |date=March 2020}}</ref> It was first proposed by the psychologists [[Jonathan Haidt]], Craig Joseph and Jesse Graham, building on the work of cultural anthropologist [[Richard Shweder]];<ref name=\"Shweder1997\">{{cite book |last1=Shweder |first1=Richard |last2=Much |first2=Nancy |last3=Mahapatra |first3=Manamohan |last4=Park |first4=Lawrence |editor1-last=Brandt |editor1-first=Allan |editor2-last=Rozin |editor2-first=Paul |title=Morality and Health |publisher=Routledge |pages=119\u2013169 |date=1997 |chapter=The \"big three\" of morality (autonomy, community, divinity) and the \"big three\" explanations of suffering.}}</ref> and subsequently developed by a diverse group of collaborators, and popularized in Haidt's book ''[[The Righteous Mind]]''.<ref name=Haidt>{{cite book|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|title=The Righteous Mind: Why Good People are Divided By Politics and Religion|year=2012|publisher=Pantheon Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0-307-37790-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/righteousmindwhy0000haid/page/9 9\u201311]|url=https://archive.org/details/righteousmindwhy0000haid/page/9}}</ref> The theory proposes six foundations: Care/Harm, Fairness/Cheating, Loyalty/Betrayal, Authority/Subversion, Sanctity/Degradation, and Liberty/Oppression;<ref name=\"Iyer2012\">{{cite journal|journal= PLOS One|last1=Iyer|first1=Ravi|first2=Spassena|last2= Koleva|first3=Jesse |last3= Graham|first4=Peter |last4= Ditto|first5=Jonathan|last5= Haidt |title= Understanding Libertarian Morality: The Psychological Dispositions of Self-Identified Libertarians|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0042366|pmid= 22927928 |pmc= 3424229|volume= 7 |issue = 8|year=2012 |page= e42366 |bibcode=2012PLoSO...742366I}}</ref><ref name=Haidt /> while its authors remain open to the addition, subtraction or modification of the set of foundations.<ref name=\"Graham2013\"/>{{rp|pages=104\u2013107}}\n\nAlthough the initial development of moral foundations theory focused on cultural differences, subsequent work with the theory has largely focused on political ideology. Various scholars have offered moral foundations theory as an explanation of differences among political [[progressives]] ([[Liberalism|liberals]] in the American sense), [[conservatives]], and [[libertarians]], and have suggested that it can explain variation in opinion on politically charged issues such as same sex marriage and abortion.<ref name=\"Koleva2012\">{{cite journal |last1=Koleva |first1=Spassena P. |last2=Graham |first2=Jesse |last3=Iyer |first3=Ravi |last4=Ditto |first4=Peter H. |last5=Haidt |first5=Jonathan |title=Tracing the threads: How five moral concerns (especially Purity) help explain culture war attitudes |journal=Journal of Research in Personality |date=April 2012 |volume=46 |issue=2 |pages=184\u2013194 |doi=10.1016/j.jrp.2012.01.006}}</ref>\n\nThe two main sources are ''The Pragmatic Validity of Moral Pluralism''<ref name=\"Graham2013\" /> and ''Mapping the Moral Domain''.<ref name=\"Graham2011\">{{cite journal |last1=Graham |first1=Jesse |last2=Nosek |first2=Brian A. |last3=Haidt |first3=Jonathan |last4=Iyer |first4=Ravi |last5=Koleva |first5=Spassena |last6=Ditto |first6=Peter H. |title=Mapping the moral domain. |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |date=2011 |volume=101 |issue=2 |pages=366\u2013385 |doi=10.1037/a0021847 |pmid=21244182 |pmc=3116962 |url=http://www-bcf.usc.edu/~jessegra/papers/GNHIKD.2011.Mapping%20the%20moral%20domain.JPSP.pdf}} {{Dead link |date=March 2020}}</ref> In the first Haidt and Graham describe their work as looking, as anthropologists, at the evolution of morality and finding the common ground between each variation. In the second they describe and defend their method, known as the Moral Foundations Questionnaire. Through various trials and a participation population that consisted of over 11,000 people, from all ages and political beliefs, they were able to find results that supported their prediction.\n\n==Origins==\nMoral foundations theory was first proposed in 2004 by Haidt and Joseph.<ref name=\"Haidt2004\" /> The theory emerged as a reaction against the developmental rationalist theory of morality associated with [[Lawrence Kohlberg]] and [[Jean Piaget]].<ref name=\"Haidt2001\">{{cite journal|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|title=The Emotional Dog and Its Rational Tail: A Social Intuitionist Approach to Moral Judgement|journal=Psychological Review|date=October 2001|volume=108|issue=4|pages=814\u201334|url=http://www.nd.edu/~wcarbona/Haidt%202001.pdf|doi=10.1037/0033-295x.108.4.814|pmid=11699120|citeseerx=10.1.1.620.5536}} {{Dead link |date=March 2020}}</ref> Building on Piaget's work, Kohlberg argued that children's moral reasoning changed over time, and proposed an explanation through his six [[Kohlberg's stages of moral development|stages of moral development]]. Kohlberg's work emphasized justice as the key concept in moral reasoning, seen as a primarily cognitive activity, and became the dominant approach to moral psychology, heavily influencing subsequent work.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Donleavy|first=Gabriel|title=No Man's Land: Exploring the Space between Gilligan and Kohlberg|journal=Journal of Business Ethics|date=July 2008|volume=80|issue=4|pages=807\u2013822|jstor=25482183|doi=10.1007/s10551-007-9470-9}}</ref><ref name=Haidt /> Haidt writes that he found Kohlberg's theories unsatisfying from the time he first encountered them in graduate school because they \"seemed too cerebral\" and lacked a focus on issues of [[emotion]].\n\nIn contrast to the dominant theories of morality in psychology, the anthropologist Richard Shweder developed a set of theories emphasizing the cultural variability of moral judgments, but argued that different cultural forms of morality drew on \"three distinct but coherent clusters of moral concerns\", which he labeled as the ethics of autonomy, community, and divinity.<ref name=\"Shweder1997\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Shweder|first=Richard|author2=Jonathan Haidt|title=Commentary to Feature Review: The Future of Moral Psychology: Truth, Intuition, and the Pluralist Way|journal=Psychological Science|date=November 1993|volume=4|issue=6|pages=360\u2013365|jstor=40062563|doi=10.1111/j.1467-9280.1993.tb00582.x}}</ref> Shweder's approach inspired Haidt to begin researching moral differences across cultures, including fieldwork in Brazil and Philadelphia. This work led Haidt to begin developing his [[Social intuitionism|social intuitionist]] approach to morality. This approach, which stood in sharp contrast to Kohlberg's rationalist work, suggested that \"moral judgment is caused by quick moral intuitions\" while moral reasoning simply serves as a post-hoc rationalization of already formed judgments.<ref name=\"Haidt2001\" /> Haidt's work and his focus on quick, intuitive, emotional judgments quickly became very influential, attracting sustained attention from an array of researchers.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Miller|first=Greg|title=The Roots of Morality|journal=Science|date=9 May 2008|volume=320|issue=5877|pages=734\u2013737|doi=10.1126/science.320.5877.734|pmid=18467565}}</ref>\n\nAs Haidt and his collaborators worked within the social intuitionist approach, they began to devote attention to the sources of the intuitions that they believed underlay moral judgments. In a 2004 article published in the journal [[Daedalus (journal)|Daedalus]],<ref name=\"Haidt2004\" /> Haidt and Joseph surveyed works on the roots of morality, including the work of [[Frans de Waal]], [[Donald Brown (anthropologist)|Donald Brown]] and Shweder, as well as [[Alan Fiske|Alan Fiske's]] [[Relational models theory|Relational Models Theory]] and [[Shalom Schwartz|Shalom Schwartz's]] [[Theory of Basic Human Values]]. From their review of these earlier lines of research, they suggested that all individuals possess four \"intuitive ethics\", stemming from the process of [[human evolution]] as responses to adaptive challenges. They labelled these four ethics as suffering, hierarchy, reciprocity, and purity.  According to Haidt and Joseph, each of the ethics formed a [[cognitive module]], whose development was shaped by culture.  They wrote that each module could \"provide little more than flashes of affect when certain patterns are encountered in the social world\", while a cultural learning process shaped each individual's response to these flashes. Morality diverges because different cultures utilize the four \"building blocks\" provided by the modules differently.<ref name=\"Haidt2004\" /> This article became the first statement of moral foundations theory, which Haidt, Joseph, and others have since elaborated and refined.\n\n==The five foundations==\nAccording to Moral Foundations Theory, differences in people's moral concerns can be described in terms of five moral foundations:\n* ''Care'': cherishing and protecting others; opposite of ''harm''\n* ''Fairness'' or ''proportionality'': rendering justice according to shared rules; opposite of ''cheating''\n* ''Loyalty'' or ''ingroup'': standing with your [[Ingroups_and_outgroups|group]], family, nation; opposite of ''betrayal''\n* ''Authority'' or ''respect'': submitting to tradition and legitimate authority; opposite of ''subversion''\n* ''Sanctity'' or ''purity'': abhorrence for disgusting things, foods, actions; opposite of ''degradation''\n\nThese five foundations are argued to group into two higher-order clusters \u2013 the person-focused ''Individualizing'' cluster of Care and Fairness, and the group-focused ''Binding'' cluster of Loyalty, Authority and Sanctity.<ref name= \"Graham2009\" /><ref name=\"Haidt&Graham2009\">{{cite book |last1=Haidt |first1=Jonathan |last2=Graham |first2=Jesse |editor1-last=Jost |editor1-first=John |editor2-last=Kay |editor2-first=Aaron |editor3-last=Thorisdottir |editor3-first=Hulda |title=Social and psychological bases of ideology and system justification |date=2009 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199869541 |pages=371\u2013401 |chapter=Planet of the Durkheimians, where community, authority, and sacredness are foundations of morality}}</ref> The empirical evidence favoring this grouping comes from patterns of associations between the moral foundations observed with the Moral Foundations Questionnaire.<ref name= \"Graham2009\" /><ref name= \"Graham2011\" />\n\nA sixth foundation, ''liberty'' (opposite of ''oppression'') was theorized by [[Jonathan Haidt]] in ''[[The Righteous Mind]]'',<ref name=Haidt /> chapter eight, in response to the need to differentiate between proportionality fairness and the objections he had received from conservatives and [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarians]] (United States usage) to coercion by a dominating power or person.<ref name=\"Iyer2012\" /> Haidt noted that the latter group's moral matrix relies almost entirely on the ''liberty'' foundation.\n\n==Methods==\nA large amount of research on Moral Foundations Theory uses self-report instruments such as the Moral Foundations Questionnaire,<ref name=\"Graham2011\" /> the Moral Foundations Sacredness Scale,<ref name=\"Graham2012\">{{cite book |last1=Graham |first1=Jesse |last2=Haidt |first2=Jonathan |editor1-last=Mikulincer |editor1-first=Mario |editor2-last=Shaver |editor2-first=Phillip R |title=The Social Psychology of Morality: Exploring the Causes of Good and Evil |date=2012 |publisher=APA Books |isbn=978-1433810114 |chapter=Sacred values and evil adversaries: A moral foundations approach}}</ref> and Moral Foundations Vignettes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Clifford |first1=Scott |last2=Iyengar |first2=Vijeth |last3=Cabeza |first3=Roberto |last4=Sinnott-Armstrong |first4=Walter |title=Moral foundations vignettes: a standardized stimulus database of scenarios based on moral foundations theory |journal=Behavior Research Methods |date=13 January 2015 |volume=47 |issue=4 |pages=1178\u20131198 |doi=10.3758/s13428-014-0551-2|pmid=25582811 |pmc=4780680 }}</ref> Research on moral language use have also relied on variants of a Moral Foundations Dictionary.<ref name=\"Graham2009\">{{cite journal |last1=Graham |first1=Jesse |last2=Haidt |first2=Jonathan |last3=Nosek |first3=Brian A. |title=Liberals and conservatives rely on different sets of moral foundations. |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |date=2009 |volume=96 |issue=5 |pages=1029\u20131046 |doi=10.1037/a0015141|pmid=19379034 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/36d3bc7659ef1dc4c8504b6a0cb82329b0ac39bf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hoover |first1=Joe |last2=Johnson |first2=Kate |last3=Boghrati |first3=Reihane |last4=Graham |first4=Jesse |last5=Dehghani |first5=Morteza |title=Moral Framing and Charitable Donation: Integrating Exploratory Social Media Analyses and Confirmatory Experimentation |journal=Collabra: Psychology |date=26 April 2018 |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=9 |doi=10.1525/collabra.129}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Matsuo |first1=Akiko |last2=Sasahara |first2=Kazutoshi |last3=Taguchi |first3=Yasuhiro |last4=Karasawa |first4=Minoru |last5=Gruebner |first5=Oliver |title=Development and validation of the Japanese Moral Foundations Dictionary |journal=PLOS One |date=25 March 2019 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=e0213343 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0213343|pmid=30908489 |pmc=6433225 |arxiv=1804.00871 }}</ref> Researchers have also examined the topographical maps of somatosensory reactions associated with violations of different moral foundations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Atari|first=Mohammad|last2=Mostafazadeh Davani|first2=Aida|last3=Dehghani|first3=Morteza|date=2020-01-08|title=Body Maps of Moral Concerns|journal=Psychological Science|volume=31|issue=2|language=en|pages=160\u2013169|doi=10.1177/0956797619895284|pmid=31913779|issn=0956-7976}}</ref> Specifically, in a study where participants were asked to describe key aspects of their subjective somatosensory experience in response to scenarios involving various moral violations, body patterns corresponding to violations of moral foundations were felt in different regions of the body depending on whether participants were liberal or conservative.\n\n==Applications==\n\n===Political ideology===\n[[File:MFQResultsExample2.jpg|thumb|Results of the Moral Foundations Questionnaire]]\nResearchers have found that people's sensitivities to the five/six moral foundations correlate with their political ideologies. Using the Moral Foundations Questionnaire, Haidt and Graham found that libertarians are most sensitive to the proposed Liberty foundation,<ref name=\"Haidt\" /> liberals are most sensitive to the Care and Fairness foundations, while conservatives are equally sensitive to all five/six foundations.<ref name=\"Graham2011\" />  [[Joshua Greene (psychologist)|Joshua Greene]] argued however that liberals tend to emphasise the Care, Fairness and Liberty dimensions; conservatives the Loyalty, Authority and Sanctity dimensions.<ref>R Sapolsky, ''Behave'' (London 2018) p. 450</ref>\n\nAccording to Haidt, the differences have significant implications for political discourse and relations. Because members of two political camps are to a degree blind to one or more of the moral foundations of the others, they may perceive morally driven words or behavior as having another basis\u2014at best self-interested, at worst evil, and thus demonize one another.<ref name=\"Moyers\">{{cite AV media\n | people = Jonathan Haidt, Bill Moyers\n | title = Jonathan Haidt Explains Our Contentious Culture\n | medium = Television production\n | publisher = Public Square Media, Inc.\n | location = Lebanon\n | date = 3 February 2012\n | url = http://billmoyers.com/segment/jonathan-haidt-explains-our-contentious-culture/}}</ref>\n\nHaidt and Graham suggest a compromise can be found to allow liberals and conservatives to see eye-to-eye.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Haidt|first=Jonathan|last2=Graham|first2=Jesse|date=2007-06-01|title=When Morality Opposes Justice: Conservatives Have Moral Intuitions that Liberals may not Recognize|journal=Social Justice Research|language=en|volume=20|issue=1|pages=98\u2013116|doi=10.1007/s11211-007-0034-z|issn=0885-7466}}</ref> They suggest that the five foundations can be used as \"doorway\" to allow liberals to step to the conservative side of the \"wall\" put up between these two political affiliations on major political issues (i.e. legalizing gay marriage). If liberals try to consider the latter three foundations in addition to the former two (therefore adopting all five foundations like conservatives for a brief amount of time) they could understand where the conservatives' viewpoints stem from and long-lasting political issues could finally be settled.\n\nResearchers postulate that the moral foundations arose as solutions to problems common in the [[Evolutionary psychology|ancestral hunter-gatherer environment]], in particular intertribal and intra-tribal conflict. The three foundations emphasized more by conservatives (Loyalty, Authority, Sanctity) bind groups together for greater strength in intertribal competition while the other two foundations balance those tendencies with concern for individuals within the group. With reduced sensitivity to the group moral foundations, progressives tend to promote a more [[universalist]] morality.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Sinn | first1 = J.S. | last2 = Hayes | first2 = M.W. | year = 2017 | title = Replacing the Moral Foundations: An Evolutionary\u2010Coalitional Theory of Liberal\u2010Conservative Differences | url = | journal = Political Psychology | volume = 38 | issue = 6| pages = 1043\u20131064 | doi=10.1111/pops.12361}}</ref>\n\n===Cross-cultural differences===\nHaidt's initial field work in Brazil and Philadelphia in 1989,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Haidt |first1=Jonathan |last2=Koller |first2=Silvia Helena |last3=Dias |first3=Maria G. |title=Affect, culture, and morality, or is it wrong to eat your dog? |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |date=1993 |volume=65 |issue=4 |pages=613\u2013628 |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.65.4.613|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/837091f3ac8cc6047833de330315e3f2c46b5af6 }}</ref> and [[Odisha]], India in 1993, showed that moralizing indeed varies among cultures, but less than by social class (e.g. education) and age. Working-class Brazilian children were more likely to consider both taboo violations and infliction of harm to be morally wrong, and universally so. Members of traditional, [[collectivist]] societies, like political conservatives, are more sensitive to violations of the community-related moral foundations. Adult members of so-called WEIRD (western, educated, industrialized, rich, and democratic) societies are the most [[individualistic]], and most likely to draw a distinction between harm-inflicting violations of morality and violations of convention.<ref name=\"Haidt\" />\n\nSubsequent investigations of moral foundations theory in other cultures have found broadly similar correlations between morality and political identification to those of the US, with studies taking place in Korea, Sweden and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Kim1\">{{cite journal|last=Kim|first=Kisok|author2=Je-Sang Kang|author3=Seongyi Yun|title=Moral intuitions and political orientation: Similarities and differences between Korea and the United States|journal=Psychological Reports|date=August 2012|volume=111|issue=1|pages=173\u2013185|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0050092|pmid=23251357|pmc=3520939}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nilsson |first1=Artur |last2=Erlandsson |first2=Arvid |title=The Moral Foundations taxonomy: Structural validity and relation to political ideology in Sweden |journal=Personality and Individual Differences |date=April 2015 |volume=76 |pages=28\u201332 |doi=10.1016/j.paid.2014.11.049}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Davies |first1=Caitlin L. |last2=Sibley |first2=Chris G. |last3=Liu |first3=James H. |title=Confirmatory Factor Analysis of the Moral Foundations Questionnaire |journal=Social Psychology |date=November 2014 |volume=45 |issue=6 |pages=431\u2013436 |doi=10.1027/1864-9335/a000201}}</ref>\n\n==Critiques and competing theories==\nA number of researchers have offered critiques of, and alternative theories to, Moral Foundations Theory. Critiques of the theory have included claims of biological implausibility<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Suhler |first1=Christopher L. |last2=Churchland |first2=Patricia |title=Can Innate, Modular \"Foundations\" Explain Morality? Challenges for Haidt's Moral Foundations Theory |journal=Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience |date=September 2011 |volume=23 |issue=9 |pages=2103\u20132116 |doi=10.1162/jocn.2011.21637|pmid=21291315 }}</ref> and redundancy among the moral foundations (which are argued to be reducible to concern about harm).<ref name=\"Schein2017\">{{cite journal |last1=Schein |first1=Chelsea |last2=Gray |first2=Kurt |title=The Theory of Dyadic Morality: Reinventing Moral Judgment by Redefining Harm |journal=Personality and Social Psychology Review |date=14 May 2017 |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=32\u201370 |doi=10.1177/1088868317698288|pmid=28504021 }}</ref> Both critiques have been disputed by the original authors.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Haidt |first1=Jonathan |last2=Joseph |first2=Craig |title=How Moral Foundations Theory Succeeded in Building on Sand: A Response to Suhler and Churchland |journal=Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience |date=September 2011 |volume=23 |issue=9 |pages=2117\u20132122 |doi=10.1162/jocn.2011.21638}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Koleva |first1=Spassena |last2=Haidt |first2=Jonathan |title=Let's Use Einstein's Safety Razor, Not Occam's Swiss Army Knife or Occam's Chainsaw |journal=Psychological Inquiry |date=April 2012 |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=175\u2013178 |doi=10.1080/1047840X.2012.667678}}</ref> Alternative theories include the Model of Moral Motives,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Janoff-Bulman |first1=Ronnie |last2=Carnes |first2=Nate C. |title=Surveying the Moral Landscape |journal=Personality and Social Psychology Review |date=16 March 2013 |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=219\u2013236 |doi=10.1177/1088868313480274|pmid=23504824 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f9a39f98565d26daeff64d205d8b450d1b0a94f4 }}</ref> the Theory of Dyadic Morality,<ref name=\"Gray2012\">{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Kurt |last2=Young |first2=Liane |last3=Waytz |first3=Adam |title=Mind Perception Is the Essence of Morality |journal=Psychological Inquiry |date=April 2012 |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=101\u2013124 |doi=10.1080/1047840X.2012.651387|pmid=22754268 |pmc=3379786 }}</ref><ref name=\"Schein2017\"/> Relationship Regulation Theory,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rai |first1=Tage Shakti |last2=Fiske |first2=Alan Page |title=Moral psychology is relationship regulation: Moral motives for unity, hierarchy, equality, and proportionality. |journal=Psychological Review |date=2011 |volume=118 |issue=1 |pages=57\u201375 |doi=10.1037/a0021867|pmid=21244187 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/30d6fd35f01cc6282b39928c5b3edfd4f836659a }}</ref> the [[right-wing authoritarianism]] scale developed by [[Bob Altemeyer]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Verhulst|first1=B.|last2=Eaves|first2=L. J.|last3=Hatemi|first3=P. K.|year=2012|title=Correlation not causation: the relationship between personality traits and political ideologies.|journal=American Journal of Political Science|volume=56|issue=1|pages=34\u201351|doi=10.1111/j.1540-5907.2011.00568.x|pmid=22400142|pmc=3809096}}</ref> and the theory of Morality As Cooperation.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Curry |first1=Oliver Scott |last2=Jones Chesters |first2=Matthew |last3=Van Lissa |first3=Caspar J. |title=Mapping morality with a compass: Testing the theory of 'morality-as-cooperation' with a new questionnaire |journal=Journal of Research in Personality |date=February 2019 |volume=78 |pages=106\u2013124 |doi=10.1016/j.jrp.2018.10.008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://moralfoundations.org/ moralfoundations.org]\n\n[[Category:Psychological theories]]\n[[Category:Psychology articles needing infoboxes]]\n[[Category:Evolutionary psychology]]\n[[Category:Moral psychology]]\n", "name_user": "Lcscnc", "label": "safe", "comment": "added citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moral_foundations_theory"}
{"title_page": "Bacon sandwich", "text_new": "{{short description|Sandwich of cooked bacon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Bacon sandwich\n| image            = Baconbutty.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = A bacon sandwich\n| alternate_name   = Bacon Banjo, Bacon butty, bacon sarnie, rasher sandwich, bacon sanger, piece 'n bacon, bacon cob, bacon barm, bacon muffin\n| country          = United Kingdom\n| region           =\n| creator          =\n| course           =\n| type             = [[Sandwich]]\n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[Bread]] and [[bacon]], with a [[condiment]], often [[ketchup]] or [[brown sauce]]\n| variations       = [[BLT]]\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n\nA '''bacon sandwich''' (also known in parts of the United Kingdom and New Zealand as a '''bacon butty''', '''bacon bap''' or '''bacon sarnie''', in Ireland as a '''rasher sandwich'''<ref name=rasher>{{cite web|last=Blog|first=Tog|title=The Rasher sandwich...|url=http://irishtogblog.blogspot.com/2009/10/rasher-sandwich.html?zx=6b225ed0fc7ab666|publisher=Togblog|accessdate=2 September 2012|date=October 2009}}</ref> and as a '''bacon sanger''' in Australia) is a [[sandwich]] of cooked [[bacon]] between bread that is optionally spread with [[butter]], and may be seasoned with [[ketchup]] or [[brown sauce]]. It is generally served hot. In some establishments the sandwich will be made from bread toasted on only one side, while other establishments serve it on the same roll as is used for hamburgers.\n\nBacon sandwiches are an all-day favourite throughout the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"cloake20120307\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/wordofmouth/2012/mar/08/how-to-cook-perfect-bacon-sandwiches | title=How to cook the perfect bacon sandwich | work=The Guardian | date=7 March 2012 | accessdate=15 January 2015 | author=Cloake, Felicity}}</ref> They are often served in [[British cafe]]s, and are anecdotally recommended as a [[hangover cure]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/5118283/Bacon-sandwich-really-does-cure-a-hangover.html|title=Bacon sandwich really does cure a hangover|date=7 April 2009|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=29 April 2013 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100107032547/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/5118283/Bacon-sandwich-really-does-cure-a-hangover.html | archive-date = 7 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Variants==\nThe [[BLT]] is a popular variant of the bacon sandwich with the additional ingredients of [[lettuce]] and [[tomato]], but served cold.<ref name=blt>{{cite web|last= Olver |first= Lynne |title=Food Timeline FAQs: sandwiches|url=http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodsandwiches.html#blt| work = FoodTimeline | date = 20 March 2015 | accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Bacon Sandwich.jpg|thumb|upright|A toasted bacon sandwich with butter and tomato ketchup]]\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Bacon, egg and cheese sandwich]]\n* [[Club sandwich]]\n* [[Chip butty]]\n* [[List of sandwiches]]\n* [[Jambon-beurre]]\n* [[Sausage sandwich]]\n* {{section link|Peameal bacon#Sandwiches}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/west_yorkshire/6538643.stm | title = Scientists 'perfect' bacon butty: Scientists have created a mathematical formula of how to make the perfect bacon butty. | work = BBC | date = 9 April 2007 | publisher = British Broadcasting Corporation}}\n{{Bacon}}\n{{Sandwiches}}\n{{Portal bar|Food}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bacon Sandwich}}\n[[Category:British sandwiches]]\n[[Category:Bacon sandwiches]]\n\n\n{{Breakfast-stub}}\n{{Bacon-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sandwich of cooked bacon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Bacon sandwich\n| image            = Baconbutty.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = A bacon sandwich\n| alternate_name   = Bacon butty, bacon sarnie, rasher sandwich, bacon sanger, piece 'n bacon, bacon cob, bacon barm, bacon muffin\n| country          = United Kingdom\n| region           =\n| creator          =\n| course           =\n| type             = [[Sandwich]]\n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[Bread]] and [[bacon]], with a [[condiment]], often [[ketchup]] or [[brown sauce]]\n| variations       = [[BLT]]\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n\nA '''bacon sandwich''' (also known in parts of the United Kingdom and New Zealand as a '''bacon butty''', '''bacon bap''' or '''bacon sarnie''', in Ireland as a '''rasher sandwich'''<ref name=rasher>{{cite web|last=Blog|first=Tog|title=The Rasher sandwich...|url=http://irishtogblog.blogspot.com/2009/10/rasher-sandwich.html?zx=6b225ed0fc7ab666|publisher=Togblog|accessdate=2 September 2012|date=October 2009}}</ref> and as a '''bacon sanger''' in Australia) is a [[sandwich]] of cooked [[bacon]] between bread that is optionally spread with [[butter]], and may be seasoned with [[ketchup]] or [[brown sauce]]. It is generally served hot. In some establishments the sandwich will be made from bread toasted on only one side, while other establishments serve it on the same roll as is used for hamburgers.\n\nBacon sandwiches are an all-day favourite throughout the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"cloake20120307\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/wordofmouth/2012/mar/08/how-to-cook-perfect-bacon-sandwiches | title=How to cook the perfect bacon sandwich | work=The Guardian | date=7 March 2012 | accessdate=15 January 2015 | author=Cloake, Felicity}}</ref> They are often served in [[British cafe]]s, and are anecdotally recommended as a [[hangover cure]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/5118283/Bacon-sandwich-really-does-cure-a-hangover.html|title=Bacon sandwich really does cure a hangover|date=7 April 2009|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=29 April 2013 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100107032547/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/5118283/Bacon-sandwich-really-does-cure-a-hangover.html | archive-date = 7 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Variants==\nThe [[BLT]] is a popular variant of the bacon sandwich with the additional ingredients of [[lettuce]] and [[tomato]], but served cold.<ref name=blt>{{cite web|last= Olver |first= Lynne |title=Food Timeline FAQs: sandwiches|url=http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodsandwiches.html#blt| work = FoodTimeline | date = 20 March 2015 | accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Bacon Sandwich.jpg|thumb|upright|A toasted bacon sandwich with butter and tomato ketchup]]\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Bacon, egg and cheese sandwich]]\n* [[Club sandwich]]\n* [[Chip butty]]\n* [[List of sandwiches]]\n* [[Jambon-beurre]]\n* [[Sausage sandwich]]\n* {{section link|Peameal bacon#Sandwiches}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/west_yorkshire/6538643.stm | title = Scientists 'perfect' bacon butty: Scientists have created a mathematical formula of how to make the perfect bacon butty. | work = BBC | date = 9 April 2007 | publisher = British Broadcasting Corporation}}\n{{Bacon}}\n{{Sandwiches}}\n{{Portal bar|Food}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bacon Sandwich}}\n[[Category:British sandwiches]]\n[[Category:Bacon sandwiches]]\n\n\n{{Breakfast-stub}}\n{{Bacon-stub}}\n", "name_user": "86.152.222.92", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacon_sandwich"}
{"title_page": "William Farrar (settler)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|Early settler, member of the Virginia Council, and Commissioner in the Virginia colony}}{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}} \n{{infobox person\n| name               = William Farrar\n| birth_date         = April 1583\n| birth_place        = [[Croxton, Lincolnshire]], England\n| death_date         = c.\u20091637\n| death_place        = [[Colonial Virginia]]\n| spouse             = [[Cecily Jordan Farrar|Cecily Jordan]]\n| occupation         = Councillor - [[Virginia Governor's Council|Council of Virginia]] and [[Virginia General Assembly]]\n}}\n\n'''William Farrar''' (April 1583 \u2013 {{Circa|1637}}) was an early [[settler]], [[Land tenure|landholder]], and [[legislator]] of the [[Colony of Virginia]]. He was a subscriber to the third charter of the [[Virginia Company]] who emigrated to the colony in 1618. After surviving the [[Powhatan attack of 1622]], he moved to [[Jordan Point, Virginia|Jordan's Journey]]. In the following year, Farrar became involved in North America's first breach of promise suit when he proposed to [[Cecily Jordan Farrar|Cecily Jordan]].  In 1626, Farrar was appointed to the [[Virginia Governor's Council|Council of Virginia]] where he served as an advisor to the royal governor, a judge of the highest court in the colony, and a member of the [[Virginia General Assembly]] of [[Colonial Jamestown]]. He was also appointed magistrate of the upper James River community. In both these roles, he served as a voice of the early planters' interest as the colony transitioned from being managed by the Virginia Company and becoming a royal colony under [[Charles I of England]]. Farrar was also on the Council when it arrested Governor [[John Harvey (Virginia)|John Harvey]] for misgovernance and forced his temporary return to England. By the time of his death around 1637, Farrar had sold off his remaining assets in England and established rights to a 2000 acre patent on [[Farrar's Island]], located on a curl of the James River.\n\n[[File:Farrar Complete Coat of Arms.jpg|thumb|The [[Coat of arms|arms]] of William Farrar's father, John Farrar of Croxton and London, Esquire<ref name= Bannerman1899/>]]\n\n==Background==\nWilliam Farrar was born before April 28, 1583,<ref name=\"Dorman2004\" /> the date of his christening, in [[Croxton, Lincolnshire]], England.<ref name=CroxtonParish1583 /> He was the 3rd son of John Farrar of Croxton<ref name= \"Bannerman1899\" /> and London, [[Esquire]], a wealthy [[merchant]] and [[Land tenure|landowner]] with various holdings in [[West Yorkshire]], [[Lincolnshire]], and [[Hertfordshire]]<ref name =Farrer1936/>, and Cecily Kelke, an heiress <ref name=Richardson2011/> and direct descendant of [[Edward III of England]].<ref name=ElleMagazine2014/> The nineteenth century historian of Virginia, [[Alexander Brown (author)|Alexander Brown]], states that while in England, William Farrar received an education in law.<ref name=Brown1890v2 />\n\n== Relation to the Virginia Company and emigration to the New World ==\n[[File:Nova Britannia Cover.jpg|thumb|left|Facsimile cover of \"Nova Britannia\", a tract from Farrar's time used to recruit people to Virginia.]]\nWhen Farrar went to Virginia, it was still part of the [[Virginia Company of London]], a [[joint-stock company]], sanctioned by [[Royal charter#United Kingdom|Royal Charter]].<ref name=\"Wolfe2016\" /> Farrar was a subscriber to the Third Charter of the Virginia Company,<ref name= Kolp2014 /> where his name appears as \"William Ferrers\".<ref name= Bemiss1957 /> His subscription consisted of three shares that were bought for a total of \u00a337 10s (equivalent to about ${{formatnum:{{ To USD round|{{inflation|UK|37.5|1600}}|GBR|sf=3}}}} today).{{Notetag|For another comparison of the share's value, the entire annual wages of a skilled [[journeyman]] in London around 1588 was authorized to be between \u00a34 and \u00a310. {{refn|name=Aughterson1998}} }}<ref name=Brown1890v2 /> Farrar also had family interests in the Virginia Company as two of his second cousins,<ref name=Torrence1942 /> the brothers [[John Ferrar]] and [[Nicholas Ferrar]], played key roles in the managing the company's interests.<ref name=Kingsbury1906v1/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini01virg_0/page/n121/mode/2up 60}} }}\n\nFarrar left London on ''Neptune''<ref name= Hotten1874/> on March 16, 1617/18  {{notetag|[[Dual dating]] is given because the English new year did not begin until March 25 during the time Virginia was colonized.  See article on [[Old Style and New Style dates#Start of the year in the historical records of Britain and its colonies and possessions|dating English historical records]] for details.}}<ref name=\"Kolb1980\" /> along with Virginia's governor, [[Thomas West, 3rd Baron De La Warr|Thomas West, Baron De La Warr]].  De La Warr had been commissioned by the Virginia Company to return to the colony with fresh people and supplies to help it achieve political and economic stability,<ref name=Brown1890v1/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/TheGenesisOfTheUnitedStatesV1/page/n499/mode/2up 375\u2013384}}}} but he died en route.<ref name=\"Billings2013\" /> When Farrar arrived in August 1618,<ref name=\"Hotten1874\"/> news of the governor's death threw [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]] into turmoil, Deputy Governor [[Samuel Argall]], who was already unpopular with many colonists, was accused of mismanagement and  the unauthorized misappropriation of  ''Neptune'''s passengers and cargo.<ref name=\"Coldham1979\"/> After a prolonged series of accusations from both the Virginia Company and colonists against Argall's governing, he finally stepped down in April 1619.<ref name=Fausz2013/>\n\nIn June 1619, the Virginia Company instructed that 40 [[Indentured Servitude#The Americas|indentured servants]] be put at the disposal of Farrar when they arrived in Virginia.<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/144/mode/2up 145}} }}  The payment for the cost of transporting these colonists would have resulted in a 2000 acre [[headright]] at 50 acres a head.<ref name=Wolfe&McCartney2015/> However, ''Garland'' never arrived in Jamestown because it was damaged in a hurricane while en route.<ref name=Coldham2002/> Instead of proceeding to Virginia, the ''Garland''{{'}}s captain, William Wye left the remaining passengers in  [[Somers Isles Company|Bermuda]] and sailed the repaired ship directly back to England.<ref name=Kingsbury1906v1 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini01virg_0/page/n645/mode/2up 325}} }}\n\nAs his personal headright, Farrar did receive a [[land patent]] for 100 acres on the [[Appomattox River]] close to where it flows into the [[James River]], near what is now known as [[Hopewell, Virginia]].<ref name= Kingsbury1935v4 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/stream/recordsofvirgini04virg/#page/n591/mode/2up 554}} }} In the meantime,  the resultant legal suits between Wye and  the Virginia Company regarding the financial responsibility for the ''Garland'' fiasco were not resolved until the end of 1622,<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/700/mode/2up 701\u2013702}}}} <ref name=Coldham2002/> when Farrar had already quit residence at his patent as a result of the [[Powhatan attack of 1622|Powhatan surprise attack of 1621/22]].\n\n== Move to Jordan's Journey and marriage==\n{{see also|Cecily Jordan v. Greville Pooley dispute}}\n\n[[File:1622 massacre jamestown de Bry.jpg|thumb|[[Matth\u00e4us Merian|Matth\u00e4us Merian's]] engraving of the Powhatan surprise attack of 1622, in which 10 people at Farrar's patent were killed.]]\nDuring the Powhatan surprise attack, ten settlers on Farrar's land on the Appomattox River were killed.<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/566/mode/2up 566}}}} However, Farrar survived and got to [[Samuel Jordan|Samuel Jordan's]] settlement at [[Jordan Point, Virginia#Beggars Bush|Beggars Bush]],<ref name=MorganEtAl1995/> part of the plantation known as [[Jordan Point, Virginia|Jordan's Journey]]. After the attack, William Farrar stayed at Jordan's Journey<ref name= McCartney2007/>{{rp|{{plainlink|{{Google books|orDbMGpInaQC|page=290|plainurl=yes}} 290\u2013291}} }} as it had become a relatively safe fortified rallying place for the survivors.<ref name=Smith1624/>\n\nSamuel Jordan died before June 1623.<ref name=Sainsbury1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/calendarstatepa16offigoog/page/n83/mode/2up 46}} }} Sometime afterward, Farrar proposed marriage to Jordan's pregnant widow, [[Cecily Jordan Farrar|Cecily]], which involved him in the  [[Cecily Jordan v. Greville Pooley dispute|first breach of promise suit filed in North America]].<ref name=Brown1890v2 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/genesisofuniteds02brow/page/n455/mode/2up 891}} }} Reverend Greville Pooley claimed he had first proposed marriage three or four days after Samuel Jordan had died and Cecily had accepted.<ref name=Kingsbury1935v4/> However, Cecily denied his proposal and accepted Farrar's, which resulted in Pooley filing the suit.<ref name =Starrett1958/>  The case continued for almost two years. During the suit, Alexander Brown suggests that Farrar may have acted as Cecily's legal representative.<ref name=Brown1890v2/>   Eventually, Pooley signed an agreement in January 1624/5 that acquitted Cecily Jordan of her alleged former promises.<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/42/mode/2up 42}}}}\n\nEven as the case was ongoing, William Farrar and Cecily Jordan continued to work together at Jordan's Journey. In November 1623, Farrar was [[debt bondage|bonded]] to execute Samuel Jordan's will regarding the management of his estate and Cecily Jordan was warranted to put down the security to guarantee Farrar's bondage.<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/8/mode/2up 8}} }} During this time, \"Farrar assumed the role of plantation 'commander' or 'head of hundred'\"<ref name=McLearenEtAl1993/>{{rp|10}} for Jordan's Journey. A year later, the Jamestown muster of 1624/25 lists \"fferrar William mr & Mrs. Jordan\"[sic] as sharing the head of a Jordan's Journey household with three daughters and ten manservants.<ref name=Hotten1874/> During this time, Jordan's Journey prospered.<ref name=Hatch1957/>{{rp|{{plainlink|http://www.gutenberg.org/files/30780/30780-h/30780-h.htm#JORDAN_R 67\u201368}} }}  By May 1625 Farrar and Jordan were finally married, as it was then that Farrar was released from his bond to Jordan's estate.<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/57/mode/2up 57}} }}They had three children together: Cecily (born 1625), William (birth year uncertain), and John (born around 1632).<ref name=Dorman2004/>\n\n== Roles in the royal colony ==\nOn March 14, 1625/6, William Farrar was appointed councillor to the [[Virginia Governor's Council#Royal colony (1624\u20131776)|Council of Virginia]] by [[Charles I of England]],<ref name=Stanard1906/> a position he held until at least 1635 when Governor [[John Harvey (Virginia)|John Harvey]] was deported.<ref name =Sainsbury1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/calendarstatepa16offigoog/page/n249/mode/2up 212\u2013213}} }}\n\n[[File:Seal of Governor's Council.png|thumb|left|Seal of \"His Majesties Council of Virginia\",\n<ref name=Brown1890v1/> the symbol of Farrar and the other councillors' role in Virginia's governance.]]\nFarrar became a councillor during a period of uncertainty for the colonists.<ref name=McCartney2007/>{{rp|{{plainlink|{{Google books|orDbMGpInaQC|page=13|plainurl=yes}} 13,}} {{plainlink|{{Google books|orDbMGpInaQC|page=35|plainurl=yes}} 35}} }} The [[Virginia Company#\"Great Charter\"|1619 Great Charter]] of the Virginia Company had established self-governance through the [[Virginia Assembly]], but [[James I]] dissolved the charter in 1624, and put the colony under direct royal authority. Just before James I died in March 1625, Charles I announced his intention to be the sole [[Factor (agent)|factor]] of his [[royal colony|royal colonies]].<ref name=Bancroft1888/> To this end, he commissioned a new structure, consisting of a governor, [[George Yeardley|Sir George Yeardley]], and 13 councillors, including William Farrar, to govern the royal colony on behalf of the Crown's interest.<ref name=\"Stanard1906\" /> Because the assembly was not included in the commission, the Council was the only legal body representing the interests of the Virginia planters.<ref name=Campbell1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/historyofcolonya00campuoft/page/180/mode/2up 180}} }} This state of affairs continued until the petitions of the colonists allowed the continuance of the [[House of Burgesses]] and the re-convention of the Virginia Assembly in 1628.<ref name= \"Brown1898\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/firstrepublicina01brow|title=The First Republic in America|last=Brown|first=Alexander|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)|publisher=Boston, MA: Houghton, Mifflin|year=1898|isbn=|pp=[https://archive.org/details/firstrepublicina01brow/page/645 645]\u2013648}}</ref> The Council also functioned as the highest court in Virginia and as the advisory board to the governor regarding the creation of legislative acts. Just as importantly, the members of the Council could determine the fate of the governor: William Farrar was on the Council when it elected [[John Pott]] as governor in 1628<ref name=Campbell1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/historyofcolonya00campuoft/page/182/mode/2up 182}} }} and he was on the Council <ref name=Brown1901/> when it arrested and temporarily deported Governor Harvey in 1635.<ref name=Bruce1894/><ref name=Tarter2017a/>\n\nIn August 1626, Farrar was also appointed by Yeardley as commissioner (i.e., [[magistrate#English common law tradition|magistrate]]) of the \"Upper Partes\"[sic]  which lies along the James River west of [[Flowerdew Hundred Plantation|Piersey's Hundred]] in the approximate area of [[Charles City County, Virginia|Charles City]] and [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico]] Counties today. Farrar was one of six commissioners appointed, however he was the one given the right of final judgement when present and allowed the discretion to hold monthly courts at either Jordan's Journey or [[Shirley Plantation|Shirley Hundred]].<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/106/mode/2up 106}} }}.  When Virginia became a crown colony, this appointment was renewed by the Governor [[John Harvey (Virginia)| Sir John Harvey]] in 1632<ref name=Hening1809/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/168 168}}}}\n\nAfter 1619, settlers could purchase the cost of transporting indentured servants from England to the new world as a contract that could redeemed as a headright, and these headright contracts could used for [[speculation]] by having them bought from, sold to, or traded with others.<ref name=Galenson1984/> William Farrar became involved in the sale of these contracts.<ref name=Southall1943/> For example, he is listed in patents as selling headrights to the settlers William Andrewes around 1628<ref name=Nugent1934/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/cavalierspioneer00nuge/page/13/mode/2up 13}} }} and Nathan Martin around 1636<ref name=Nugent1934/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/cavalierspioneer00nuge/page/41/mode/2up 41}} }}\n\n== Sale of inheritance ==\nWhen William Farrar's father, John the elder, died sometime before May 1628, he willed his various landholdings in Hertfordshire to William. In addition, John Farrar also stipulated that William and his family receive a \u00a320 annuity from his older brother from rents in Halifax Parish, Yorkshire and that William receive \u00a350 upon his return to England.<ref name= \"Farrer1936\"/> In 1631,  William Farrar returned to England to claim his inheritance.<ref name=McCartney2007/>  He then sold the assets from his inheritance to his brothers, including his annuity for \u00a3240 and his landholdings for \u00a3200, for a total of \u00a3440 (equivalent to about ${{formatnum:{{ To USD round|{{inflation|UK|440|1600}}|GBR|sf=3}}}} today)<ref name=Holmes1972/> and returned to Virginia.\n\n==Farrar's Island==\n[[File:Map of William Farrar&#039;s Patent for Farrar&#039;s Island and Environs.jpg|thumb|Approximate extent of William Farrar&#039;s 2000-acre land grant including Farrar&#039;s Island and environs as defined by 1637 patent]]\nAt the time of his death sometime before June 11, 1637, Farrar was described as being \"of Henrico\"<ref name=Nugent1934/>, one of eight [[shire|shires]] established in Virginia three years previously.<ref name=Hening1809/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/224 224}}}}  By the time of his death, he had established his headright to a 2000 acre land patent at a site that included [[Dutch Gap]] and the former settlement of [[Henricus|Henrico]]. This headright was given for 40 indentured servants, who were named in the patent.{{notetag|At least seven of the names of the patents were those of people listed as living with Farrar and Jordan in the Muster of 1624/1625,{{refn|name=Southall1943}}}} After Farrar's death, the headright was repatented to his oldest son,<ref name=McCartney2011/> his namesake who was twelve years old at the time, by John Harvey, who had returned from England and resumed his role as governor of the colony.<ref name= Tarter2017b/>\n\nThe patent was issued for land that included a peninsula formed by [[meander]] loop, or curl,<ref name = McJimsey1940/> of the James River subsequently known as [[Farrar's Island]]. It is described in the patent as abutting the [[glebe]] lands of [[Varina Farms|Varina]] in the east,{{notetag|The glebe of Varina's boundaries were mapped during an archaeological study performed just before the construction of the [[Varina-Enon Bridge]] at the glebe's former location.<ref name=Geier&McCartney2018/>}} and extending to the James River in the south, the end of the island (i.e., peninsula) in the west, and \"to the woods\" in the north.<ref name=Nugent1934/>  Farrar's Island remained with the Farrar family until it was sold in 1731.<ref name=Stanard1901/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notefoot}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Aughterson1998>{{cite book|editor=Aughterson, Kate|title=The English Renaissance: An Anthology of Sources and Documents|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uopDaWjyyekC&q=Westminster+#v=onepage&q=Westminster%2024%20August%201588&f=false|publisher=New York, NY: Routledge|year=1998|isbn=9780415271158|pp=201\u2013202}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bancroft1888>{{cite book|title=History of the United States of America, Vol. I|author=Bancroft, George|author-link=George Bancroft|publisher=New York, NY: D. Appleton|date=1888|page=[https://archive.org/details/historyoftheunit037605mbp/page/n169 135]|url=https://archive.org/details/historyoftheunit037605mbp}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bannerman1899>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/visitationsofcou43beno |title=The Visitations of the County of Surrey: Made and Taken in the Years 1530 by Thomas Benolte, Clarenceux King of Arms; 1572 by Robert Cooke, Clarenceux King of Arms; and 1623 by Samuel Thomson, Windsor Herald and Augustin Vincent, Rouge Croix Pursuivant, Marshals and Deputies to William Camden, Clarenceux King of Arms|year=1899|pp=[https://archive.org/details/visitationsofcou43beno/page/157 157]\u2013158|publisher= London: Ye Wardour|editor=Bannerman, W. Bruce}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bemiss1957>{{cite book|title=The Three Charters of the Virginia Company of London with Seven Related Documents|chapter=Third Charter| editor=Bemiss, Samuel M.|date=1957|publisher=Williamsburg, VA: Virginia 350th Anniversary Celebration Corporation|chapter-url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/36181/36181-h/36181-h.htm#pg_7|page=7}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Billings2013>{{cite web|last=Billings, Warren M.|date=27 October 2013|access-date=21 Dec 2018|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/West_Thomas_twelfth_baron_De_La_Warr_1577-1618|title= Thomas West, twelfth baron De La Warr (1576\u20131618)|website= Encyclopedia Virginia|publisher=Virginia Foundation for the Humanities}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Brown1890v1>{{cite book|author=Brown, Alexander|date=1890|title=Genesis of the United States, Vol. 1|publisher=New York: Houghton, Mifflin|page=[https://archive.org/details/TheGenesisOfTheUnitedStatesV1/page/n116 57]|url=https://archive.org/details/TheGenesisOfTheUnitedStatesV1|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Brown1890v2>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/genesisofuniteds02brow/page/n455|title=The Genesis of the United States, Vol 2|last=Brown|first=Alexander|date=1890|publisher=Boston, MA Houghton, Mifflin|page=[https://archive.org/details/genesisofuniteds02brow/page/n455 691]|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Brown1898\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/firstrepublicina01brow|title=The First Republic in America|last=Brown|first=Alexander|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)|publisher=Boston, MA: Houghton, Mifflin|year=1898|isbn=|pp=[https://archive.org/details/firstrepublicina01brow/page/645 645]\u2013648}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Brown1901>{{Cite book | last=Brown | first=Alexander|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)|title=English Politics in Early Virginia History |publication-date=1901 | publisher=Boston, MA: Houghton Mifflin |date=1901|page=[https://archive.org/details/englishpoliticsi00brow/page/100 100] | url=https://archive.org/details/englishpoliticsi00brow| quote=English politics in early virginia history William Ferrar. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bruce1894>{{cite journal |title= Mutiny in Virginia, 1635|editor= Bruce, Philip A.|author-link=Philip Alexander Bruce|url=https://archive.org/details/virginiamagazine01virguoft/page/418|journal=Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume=1|year=1894|issue=4|page=419}}</ref>\n\n<ref name= Campbell1860>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofcolonya00campuoft/page/180|title=History of Colony and Ancient Dominion of Virginia|last=Campbell|first=Charles|publisher=J.Philadelphia, PA: B. Lippincott|year=1860}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Coldham1979\">{{cite journal |last=Coldham, Peter Wilson|author-link=Peter Wilson Coldham|date= 1979|title= The voyage of the Neptune to Virginia 1618-1619, and the Disposition of its cargo |jstor=4248277 |journal=The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography |volume=87 |issue=1 |pages=30\u201367}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Coldham2002>{{cite book|author=Coldham, Peter Wilson|author-link=Peter Wilson Coldham|title=English Adventurers and Emigrants, 1609-1660: Abstracts of Examinations in the High Court of Admiralty with Reference to Colonial America|pages=5-6|publisher=Baltimore, MD: Genealogical Publishing|date=2002|isbn=9780806310824|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/englishadventure00cold}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=CroxtonParish1583>{{cite web|title=Croxton Parish Records- Marriages, Baptisms & Burials (1583)|website= Lincs to the Past, Lincolnshire Archives|url=https://www.lincstothepast.com/Records/RecordDisplayTranscript.aspx?oid=723828&iid=180376|date=December 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Dorman2004>{{cite book | editor-last=Dorman, John Frederick | title=Adventurers of Purse and Person, Virginia, 1607\u20131624/5: Families A-F (Volume 1)| date=2004 | publisher=Baltimore, MD: Genealogical Publishing | edition= 4th.|pp=926\u2013928|isbn=978-0806317441}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ElleMagazine2014>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.elle.com.au/celebrity/so-turns-out-the-fanning-sisters-are-royals-3452|magazine=Elle Australia|title=So, turns out the Fanning sisters are royals|date= 28 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030210130/https://www.elle.com.au/celebrity/so-turns-out-the-fanning-sisters-are-royals-3452|archive-date=30 Oct 2019|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Fausz2013>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Argall_Samuel_bap_1580-1626|title=Samuel Argall (bap. 1580-1626)|author= Fausz, J. Frederick|date=July 8, 2013|website=Encyclopedia Virginia: Virginia Humanities|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115182012/https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Argall_Samuel_bap_1580-1626|archive-date=January 15, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n.<ref name =Farrer1936>{{cite book|title=Farrer (and Some Variants) Wills and Administrations : So Far Discovered by Me in England and Wales, and the Isle of Man Down to A.D. 1800|author=Farrer, Thomas C. F|author-link= Thomas Farrer, 2nd Baron Farrer|date=1936|publisher=Dorking, England: Tanner and Son|pp=[https://archive.org/details/farrerandsomevar00farr/page/126 126]\u2013128|url=https://archive.org/details/farrerandsomevar00farr}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Galenson1984>{{cite journal |last=Galenson, David W.|author-link=David Galenson|date= 1984|title= The rise and fall of indentured servitude in the Americas: An economic analysis|jstor=2120553 |journal=The Journal of Economic History |volume=44 |issue=1 |page=10}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Geier&McCartney2018>{{Cite book|title=The Henrico Parish Glebe, Varina, Virginia: 44HE229, A Multidisciplinary Case Study|author1=Geier, Clarence R.|author2=McCartney, Martha W.|author2-link=Martha W. McCartney|volume=Special Publication no. 45|publisher=Richmond,VA:Archeological Society of Virginia|ISBN=1981435816|year=2018|page=3}}</ref>\n\n<ref name= Hatch1957>{{ Cite book |author= Hatch, Charles E.|year=1957|title=The First Seventeen Years: Virginia, 1607-1624|publisher=Williamsburg, VA: Jamestown 350th Anniversary Celebration Corp.|page=68|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/30780/30780-h/30780-h.htm#JORDAN_R}}</ref>\n\n<ref name= Hening1809>{{cite book|title= The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia, from the First Session of the Legislature, in the year 1619. Published Pursuant to an Act of the General Assembly of Virginia|editor= Hening, William Waller|date=1809|publisher= Richmond, VA: Samuel Pleasants, Jr., printer to the common wealth.|page=[https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/168 168]|url=https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg|editor-link=William Waller Hening}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Holmes1972>Sale of William Farrar's Inheritance\u201d''recorded at the [[Public Record Office]]: London, Calendar of [[Close Roll]]s.'' Vol 54/2904, cited in {{Cite book | last=Holmes | first=Alvahn | title=The Farrar's Island Family and its English Ancestry | date=1972 | publisher=Baltimore, MD: Gateway Press |p=31| oclc=499544604 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Hotten1874>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/originallistsofp00hottuoft|title=The Original Lists of Persons of Quality, Emigrants, Religious Exiles, Political Rebels, Serving Men Sold for a Term of Years; Apprentices; Children stolen; Maidens Pressed; and Others Who Went from Great Britain to the American Plantations, 1600-1700 : With Their Ages and the Names of the Ships in Which they Embarked, and other Interesting Particulars; from Mss. Preserved in the State Paper Department of Her Majesty's Public Record Office, England|author=Hotten, John Camden|date=1874|publisher=New York, NY: Empire State Book|pages=[https://archive.org/details/originallistsofp00hottuoft/page/222 209]\u2013210|author-link=John Camden Hotten}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Kingsbury1906v1>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini01virg_0/page/n121|title=The Records of the Virginia Company of London|date=1906|publisher=Washington DC: Government Printing Office|editor=Kingsbury, Susan M.|editor-link=Susan Myra Kingsbury| volume=1}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/144|title=Records of the Virginia Company of London|volume=3|editor=Kingsbury, Susan Myra|editor-link=Susan Myra Kingsbury|publisher=Washington DC: Government Printing Office|date=1933}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Kingsbury1935v4>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/recordsofvirgini04virg/#page/n591/mode/2up|title=The Records of the Virginia Company of London|date=1935|publisher=Washington DC: Government Printing Office|editor=Kingsbury, Susan M.|editor-link=Susan Myra Kingsbury|volume=4}}</ref>\n\n<ref name =Kolp2014>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Third_Charter_of_Virginia_1612|editor= Kolp, John|title=Primary Resource: Third Charter of Virginia (1612)|date=June 26, 2014|website=Encyclopedia Virginia|publisher=Virginia Humanities|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522084212/http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Third_Charter_of_Virginia_1612#|archive-date=May 22, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=November 7, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Kolb1980>{{cite journal |last=Kolb, Avery E.|date= 1980|title= Early passengers to Virginia: When did they really arrive? |jstor=4248428 |journal=The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography |volume=88 |issue=4 |pages= 401\u2013414}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=McCartney2007>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=orDbMGpInaQC&pg=PA290&lpg=PA290&dq=capt+william+wye+farrar#v=onepage&q=capt%20william%20wye%20farrar&f=false|title=Virginia Immigrants and Adventurers, 1607-1635|last=McCartney|first=Martha W.|author-link=Martha W. McCartney|date=2007|publisher= Baltimore, MD: Genealogical Publishing|isbn=9780806317748}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=McCartney2011>{{cite book |author=McCartney, Martha W.|title=Jordan's Point, Virginia: Archaeology in Perspective, Prehistoric to Modern Times|publisher=University of Virginia Press|year=2011|author-link=Martha W. McCartney}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=McIlwaine1924>{{cite book|editor=McIlwaine, H. R. |editor-link=Henry Read McIlwaine|date=1924|title=Minutes of the Council and General Court of Colonial Virginia 1622-1632, 1670-1676 with Notes and Excerpts from Original Council and General Court Records into 1683, Now Lost|publisher=Richmond, VA: Virginia State Library|url=https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/8}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=McJimsey1940>{{cite journal |last=McJimsey, George Davis|date= 1940|title= Topographical Terms in Virginia (II) |jstor=486821 |journal=American Speech |volume=88 |issue=2 |page= 169}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=McLearenEtAl1993>{{cite book|author1=McLearen, Douglas C. |author2=Mouer, L. Daniel|author3=Boyd, Donna M.|author4= Owsley, Douglas W.|author5= Compton, Bertita|year=1993|title=Jordan's Journey: A Preliminary Report on the 1992 Excavations at Archaeological Sites 44PG302, 44PG303, and 44PG315|publisher= Richmond, VA: Virginia Commonwealth University Archaeological Research Center|doi=10.6067/XCV81J98NK|url=https://core.tdar.org/document/6083/jordans-journey-a-preliminary-report-on-the-1992-excavations-at-archaeological-sites-44pg302-44pg303-and-44pg315}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=MorganEtAl1995>{{cite book|last1=Morgan|first1=Tim|last2=Luccketti|first2=Nicholas|last3=Straube|first3=Beverly|last4=Bessey|first4=S. Fiona|last5=Loomis|first5=Annette|last6=Hodges|first6=Charles|date=1995|title=Archaeological Excavations at Jordan's Point: Sites 44PG151, 44PG300, 44PG302, 44PG303, 44PG315, 44PG333|publisher= Richmond, VA: Virginia Department of Historic Resources|doi=10.6067/XCV8H41QBZ|url=https://core.tdar.org/document/6084/archaeological-excavations-at-jordans-point-sites-44pg151-44pg300-44pg302-44pg303-44pg315-44pg333|page=4}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Nugent1934>{{cite book|author=Nugent, Nell Marion|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/cavalierspioneer00nuge/page/60|title=Cavaliers and Pioneers, a Calendar of Land Grants 1623-1800|volume=1|date=1934|chapter=Patent Book No. 1|publisher=Richmond, VA: Dietz Press}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Richardson2011>{{cite book|author=Richardson, Douglas|title=Plantagenet Ancestry: A Study in Colonial and Medieval families|edition=2|page=30|volume=2|publisher=Scotts Valley, CA: CreateSpace|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kjme027UeagC&pg=PA787#v=onepage&q=Kelke&f=false}}</ref>\n\n<ref name =Sainsbury1860>{{cite book|title=Calendar of State Papers Colonial, America and West Indies: Volume 1, 1574-1660|editor=Sainsbury, W. Noel|date=1860|publisher=London, England: Longman, Green Longman & Roberts|url=https://archive.org/details/calendarstatepa16offigoog/page/n249}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Smith1624>{{cite book|editor=Arber, Edward|editor-link=Edward Arber|url=https://archive.org/details/travelsworksofca02smit/page/584/mode/2up/|title=Travels and Works of Captain John Smith|volume=Part II| chapter=The Generall Historie of Virginia, the Fourth Booke|last=Smith|first=John|orig-year=1624|year=1910|page=584|publisher=Edinburgh, Scotland: John Grant|author-link=John Smith (explorer)}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Southall1943>{{cite journal|author= Southall, James P. C.|title= Links in a Chain|journal=Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume = 51|issue = 4|page = 386|jstor = 4242430|year = 1943}}</ref> \n\n<ref name=Stanard1901>{{cite journal|author= Stanard, William G.|title= Farrar Family|journal=Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume = 9|issue = 2|page = 203|jstor = 4242430|year = 1901}}</ref> \n\n<ref name=Stanard1906>{{cite journal |title= Commission to Governor Yeardley and Council, March 14 1625-6|editor= Stanard, William G. |jstor=4242747|journal=Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume=13|year=1906|issue=3|pages = 298\u2013302}}</ref>\n\n<ref name =Starrett1958>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23506275/breach_of_promise_case_at_jamestown_va/|title=America's First Breach of Promise Case|last=Starrett|first=Vincent|date=March 3, 1958|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Tarter2017a>{{cite web|last=Tarter, Brent|date= 13 March 2017|title= Sir John Harvey (ca. 1581 or 1582\u2013by 1650) |website= Encyclopedia Virginia|publisher=Virginia Foundation for the Humanities|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Harvey_Sir_John_ca_1581_or_1582-by_1650|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221134542/https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Harvey_Sir_John_ca_1581_or_1582-by_1650|archive-date=Dec 21, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 16, 2019|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Tarter2017b>{{cite journal |last=Tarter, Brent|author-link=David Galenson|date= 1984|title= Sir John Harvey: Royal Governor of Virginia, 1628\u20131639|jstor=26322580|journal=The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography |volume=125 |issue=1 |page=23}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Torrence1942\">{{cite journal |title=English Ancestry of William Farrar (1594-C.1637), of Henrico County, Virginia|journal=The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume=50|issue=4|pages=350\u2013359|author-last1=Torrence, Clayton, ed.|author-last2=Cook, Mrs. Henry Lowell|author-last3=Bulkley, Louis C.|year=1942|jstor=4245205}}</ref>\n\n.<ref name=Wolfe2016>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Virginia_Company_of_London|title=Virginia Company of London|website=Encyclopedia Virginia|publisher=Virginia Foundation for the Humanities| author=Wolfe, Brenden|date=2016-11-16|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813020737/https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Virginia_Company_of_London|archive-date=August 13, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=2018-11-05|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Wolfe&McCartney2015>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Indentured_Servants_in_Colonial_Virginia|author1=Wolfe, Brendan|author2=McCartney, Martha|title=Indentured Servants in Colonial Virginia|date=Oct 28, 2015|website=Encyclopedia Virginia|publisher=Virginia Humanities|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213120206/https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Indentured_Servants_in_Colonial_Virginia|archive-date=Dec 13, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 16, 2019|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Further reading===\n*{{Cite book | last=Holmes | first=Alvahn | title=The Farrar's Island Family and its English Ancestry | date=1972 | publisher=Baltimore, MD: Gateway Press | oclc=499544604 }}\n*Stanard, William G., ed. (1900-1902) The \"Farrar Family\" Excursus in ''The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography''\n**{{cite journal|title= The Farrar Family|journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography |volume= 7 |issue= 3 |pages= 319\u2013322 |jstor= 4242269 |year= 1900 }}, \n**{{cite journal|title= The Farrar Family (Continued)|journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume= 7|issue= 4|pages= 432\u2013434|jstor= 4242292|year= 1900}} \n**{{cite journal|title= The Farrar Family (Continued)|journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume= 8|issue= 1|pages= 97\u201398|jstor= 4242320|year= 1900}}\n**{{cite journal|title= The Farrar Family (Continued)|journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume= 8|issue= 2|pages= 206\u2013209|jstor= 4242337|year= 1900}}\n**{{cite journal|title= The Farrar Family (Continued)|journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume= 8|issue= 4|pages= 424\u2013427|jstor= 4242386|year= 1901}}\n**{{cite journal|title= The Farrar Family (Continued)|journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume= 9|issue= 2|pages= 203\u2013205|jstor= 4242430|year= 1901}}\n**{{cite journal|title= The Farrar Family (Continued)|journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume= 9|issue= 3|pages= 322\u2013324|jstor= 4242449|year= 1902}}\n**{{cite journal|title= The Farrar Family (Continued)|journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume= 10|issue= 1|pages= 86\u201387|jstor= 4242488|year= 1902}}\n**{{cite journal|title= The Farrar Family (Continued)|journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume= 10|issue= 2|pages= 206\u2013207|jstor= 4242519|year= 1902}}\n**{{cite journal|title= The Farrar Family (Continued)|journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume= 10|issue= 3|pages= 308\u2013310|jstor= 4242543|year= 1902}}.\n(''Note'': The Vol. 7(4) entry in the excursus is incorrect on William Farrar's lineage. See {{cite journal| title= Torrence et al., 1942| journal= The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography| volume= 50| issue= 4| pages= 350\u2013359| jstor= 4245205| year= 1942}} referenced above.)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farrar, William}}\n[[Category:1583 births]]\n[[Category:1637 deaths]]\n[[Category:History of Virginia]]\n[[Category:First Families of Virginia]]\n[[Category:Virginia colonial people]]\n[[Category:People from Virginia]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|Early settler, member of the Virginia Council, and Commissioner in the Virginia colony}}{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}} \n{{infobox person\n| name               = William Farrar\n| birth_date         = April 1583\n| birth_place        = [[Croxton, Lincolnshire]], England\n| death_date         = c.\u20091637\n| death_place        = [[Colonial Virginia]]\n| spouse             = [[Cecily Jordan Farrar|Cecily Jordan]]\n| occupation         = Councillor - [[Virginia Governor's Council|Council of Virginia]] and [[Virginia General Assembly]]\n}}\n\n'''William Farrar''' (April 1583 \u2013 {{Circa|1637}}) was an early [[settler]], [[Land tenure|landholder]], and [[legislator]] of the [[Colony of Virginia]]. He was a subscriber to the third charter of the [[Virginia Company]] who emigrated to the colony in 1618. After surviving the [[Powhatan attack of 1622]], he moved to [[Jordan Point, Virginia|Jordan's Journey]]. In the following year, Farrar became involved in North America's first breach of promise suit when he proposed to [[Cecily Jordan Farrar|Cecily Jordan]].  In 1626, Farrar was appointed to the [[Virginia Governor's Council|Council of Virginia]] where he served as an advisor to the royal governor, a judge of the highest court in the colony, and a member of the [[Virginia General Assembly]] of [[Colonial Jamestown]]. He was also appointed magistrate of the upper James River community. In both these roles, he served as a voice of the early planters' interest as the colony transitioned from being managed by the Virginia Company and becoming a royal colony under [[Charles I of England]]. Farrar was also on the Council when it arrested Governor [[John Harvey (Virginia)|John Harvey]] for misgovernance and forced his temporary return to England. By the time of his death around 1637, Farrar had sold off his remaining assets in England and established rights to a 2000 acre patent on [[Farrar's Island]], located on a curl of the James River.\n\n[[File:Farrar Complete Coat of Arms.jpg|thumb|The [[Coat of arms|arms]] of William Farrar's father, John Farrar of Croxton and London, Esquire<ref name= Bannerman1899/>]]\n\n==Background==\nWilliam Farrar was born before April 28, 1583,<ref name=\"Dorman2004\" /> the date of his christening, in [[Croxton, Lincolnshire]], England.<ref name=CroxtonParish1583 /> He was the 3rd son of John Farrar of Croxton<ref name= \"Bannerman1899\" /> and London, [[Esquire]], a wealthy [[merchant]] and [[Land tenure|landowner]] with various holdings in [[West Yorkshire]], [[Lincolnshire]], and [[Hertfordshire]]<ref name =Farrer1936/>, and Cecily Kelke, an heiress <ref name=Richardson2011/> and direct descendant of [[Edward III of England]].<ref name=ElleMagazine2014/> The nineteenth century historian of Virginia, [[Alexander Brown (author)|Alexander Brown]], states that while in England, William Farrar received an education in law.<ref name=Brown1890v2 />\n\n== Relation to the Virginia Company and emigration to the New World ==\n[[File:Nova Britannia Cover.jpg|thumb|left|Facsimile cover of \"Nova Britannia\", a tract from Farrar's time used to recruit people to Virginia.]]\nWhen Farrar went to Virginia, it was still part of the [[Virginia Company of London]], a [[joint-stock company]], sanctioned by [[Royal charter#United Kingdom|Royal Charter]].<ref name=\"Wolfe2016\" /> Farrar was a subscriber to the Third Charter of the Virginia Company,<ref name= Kolp2014 /> where his name appears as \"William Ferrers\".<ref name= Bemiss1957 /> His subscription consisted of three shares that were bought for a total of \u00a337 10s (equivalent to about ${{formatnum:{{ To USD round|{{inflation|UK|37.5|1600}}|GBR|sf=3}}}} today).{{Notetag|For another comparison of the share's value, the entire annual wages of a skilled [[journeyman]] in London around 1588 was authorized to be between \u00a34 and \u00a310. {{refn|name=Aughterson1998}} }}<ref name=Brown1890v2 /> Farrar also had family interests in the Virginia Company as two of his second cousins,<ref name=Torrence1942 /> the brothers [[John Ferrar]] and [[Nicholas Ferrar]], played key roles in the managing the company's interests.<ref name=Kingsbury1906v1/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini01virg_0/page/n121/mode/2up 60}} }}\n\nFarrar left London on ''Neptune''<ref name= Hotten1874/> on March 16, 1617/18  {{notetag|[[Dual dating]] is given because the English new year did not begin until March 25 during the time Virginia was colonized.  See article on [[Old Style and New Style dates#Start of the year in the historical records of Britain and its colonies and possessions|dating English historical records]] for details.}}<ref name=\"Kolb1980\" /> along with Virginia's governor, [[Thomas West, 3rd Baron De La Warr|Thomas West, Baron De La Warr]].  De La Warr had been commissioned by the Virginia Company to return to the colony with fresh people and supplies to help it achieve political and economic stability,<ref name=Brown1890v1/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/TheGenesisOfTheUnitedStatesV1/page/n499/mode/2up 375\u2013384}}}} but he died en route.<ref name=\"Billings2013\" /> When Farrar arrived in August 1618,<ref name=\"Hotten1874\"/> news of the governor's death threw [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]] into turmoil, Deputy Governor [[Samuel Argall]], who was already unpopular with many colonists, was accused of mismanagement and  the unauthorized misappropriation of  ''Neptune'''s passengers and cargo.<ref name=\"Coldham1979\"/> After a prolonged series of accusations from both the Virginia Company and colonists against Argall's governing, he finally stepped down in April 1619.<ref name=Fausz2013/>\n\nIn June 1619, the Virginia Company instructed that 40 [[Indentured Servitude#The Americas|indentured servants]] be put at the disposal of Farrar when they arrived in Virginia.<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/144/mode/2up 145}} }}  The payment for the cost of transporting these colonists would have resulted in a 2000 acre [[headright]] at 50 acres a head.<ref name=Wolfe&McCartney2015/> However, ''Garland'' never arrived in Jamestown because it was damaged in a hurricane while en route.<ref name=Coldham2002/> Instead of proceeding to Virginia, the ''Garland''{{'}}s captain, William Wye left the remaining passengers in  [[Somers Isles Company|Bermuda]] and sailed the repaired ship directly back to England.<ref name=Kingsbury1906v1 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini01virg_0/page/n645/mode/2up 325}} }}\n\nAs his personal headright, Farrar did receive a [[land patent]] for 100 acres on the [[Appomattox River]] close to where it flows into the [[James River]], near what is now known as [[Hopewell, Virginia]].<ref name= Kingsbury1935v4 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/stream/recordsofvirgini04virg/#page/n591/mode/2up 554}} }} In the meantime,  the resultant legal suits between Wye and  the Virginia Company regarding the financial responsibility for the ''Garland'' fiasco were not resolved until the end of 1622,<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/700/mode/2up 701\u2013702}}}} <ref name=Coldham2002/> when Farrar had already quit residence at his patent as a result of the [[Powhatan attack of 1622|Powhatan surprise attack of 1621/22]].\n\n== Move to Jordan's Journey and marriage==\n{{see also|Cecily Jordan v. Greville Pooley dispute}}\n\n[[File:1622 massacre jamestown de Bry.jpg|thumb|[[Matth\u00e4us Merian|Matth\u00e4us Merian's]] engraving of the Powhatan surprise attack of 1622, in which 10 people at Farrar's patent were killed.]]\nDuring the Powhatan surprise attack, ten settlers on Farrar's land on the Appomattox River were killed.<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/566/mode/2up 566}}}} However, Farrar survived and got to [[Samuel Jordan|Samuel Jordan's]] settlement at [[Jordan Point, Virginia#Beggars Bush|Beggars Bush]],<ref name=MorganEtAl1995/> part of the plantation known as [[Jordan Point, Virginia|Jordan's Journey]]. After the attack, William Farrar stayed at Jordan's Journey<ref name= McCartney2007/>{{rp|{{plainlink|{{Google books|orDbMGpInaQC|page=290|plainurl=yes}} 290\u2013291}} }} as it had become a relatively safe fortified rallying place for the survivors.<ref name=Smith1624/>\n\nSamuel Jordan died before June 1623.<ref name=Sainsbury1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/calendarstatepa16offigoog/page/n83/mode/2up 46}} }} Sometime afterward, Farrar proposed marriage to Jordan's pregnant widow, [[Cecily Jordan Farrar|Cecily]], which involved him in the  [[Cecily Jordan v. Greville Pooley dispute|first breach of promise suit filed in North America]].<ref name=Brown1890v2 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/genesisofuniteds02brow/page/n455/mode/2up 891}} }} Reverend Greville Pooley claimed he had first proposed marriage three or four days after Samuel Jordan had died and Cecily had accepted.<ref name=Kingsbury1935v4/> However, Cecily denied his proposal and accepted Farrar's, which resulted in Pooley filing the suit.<ref name =Starrett1958/>  The case continued for almost two years. During the suit, Alexander Brown suggests that Farrar may have acted as Cecily's legal representative.<ref name=Brown1890v2/>   Eventually, Pooley signed an agreement in January 1624/5 that acquitted Cecily Jordan of her alleged former promises.<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/42/mode/2up 42}}}}\n\nEven as the case was ongoing, William Farrar and Cecily Jordan continued to work together at Jordan's Journey. In November 1623, Farrar was [[debt bondage|bonded]] to execute Samuel Jordan's will regarding the management of his estate and Cecily Jordan was warranted to put down the security to guarantee Farrar's bondage.<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/8/mode/2up 8}} }} During this time, \"Farrar assumed the role of plantation 'commander' or 'head of hundred'\"<ref name=McLearenEtAl1993/>{{rp|10}} for Jordan's Journey. A year later, the Jamestown muster of 1624/25 lists \"fferrar William mr & Mrs. Jordan\"[sic] as sharing the head of a Jordan's Journey household with three daughters and ten manservants.<ref name=Hotten1874/> During this time, Jordan's Journey prospered.<ref name=Hatch1957/>{{rp|{{plainlink|http://www.gutenberg.org/files/30780/30780-h/30780-h.htm#JORDAN_R 67\u201368}} }}  By May 1625 Farrar and Jordan were finally married, as it was then that Farrar was released from his bond to Jordan's estate.<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/57/mode/2up 57}} }}They had three children together: Cecily (born 1625), William (birth year uncertain), and John (born around 1632).<ref name=Dorman2004/>\n\n== Roles in the royal colony ==\nOn March 14, 1625/6, William Farrar was appointed councillor to the [[Virginia Governor's Council#Royal colony (1624\u20131776)|Council of Virginia]] by [[Charles I of England]],<ref name=Stanard1906/> a position he held until at least 1635 when Governor [[John Harvey (Virginia)|John Harvey]] was deported.<ref name =Sainsbury1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/calendarstatepa16offigoog/page/n249/mode/2up 212\u2013213}} }}\n\n[[File:Seal of Governor's Council.png|thumb|left|Seal of \"His Majesties Council of Virginia\",\n<ref name=Brown1890v1/> the symbol of Farrar and the other councillors' role in Virginia's governance.]]\nFarrar became a councillor during a period of uncertainty for the colonists.<ref name=McCartney2007/>{{rp|{{plainlink|{{Google books|orDbMGpInaQC|page=13|plainurl=yes}} 13,}} {{plainlink|{{Google books|orDbMGpInaQC|page=35|plainurl=yes}} 35}} }} The [[Virginia Company#\"Great Charter\"|1619 Great Charter]] of the Virginia Company had established self-governance through the [[Virginia Assembly]], but [[James I]] dissolved the charter in 1624, and put the colony under direct royal authority. Just before James I died in March 1625, Charles I announced his intention to be the sole [[Factor (agent)|factor]] of his [[royal colony|royal colonies]].<ref name=Bancroft1888/> To this end, he commissioned a new structure, consisting of a governor, [[George Yeardley|Sir George Yeardley]], and 13 councillors, including William Farrar, to govern the royal colony on behalf of the Crown's interest.<ref name=\"Stanard1906\" /> Because the assembly was not included in the commission, the Council was the only legal body representing the interests of the Virginia planters.<ref name=Campbell1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/historyofcolonya00campuoft/page/180/mode/2up 180}} }} This state of affairs continued until the petitions of the colonists allowed the continuance of the [[House of Burgesses]] and the re-convention of the Virginia Assembly in 1628.<ref name= \"Brown1898\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/firstrepublicina01brow|title=The First Republic in America|last=Brown|first=Alexander|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)|publisher=Boston, MA: Houghton, Mifflin|year=1898|isbn=|pp=[https://archive.org/details/firstrepublicina01brow/page/645 645]\u2013648}}</ref> The Council also functioned as the highest court in Virginia and as the advisory board to the governor regarding the creation of legislative acts. Just as importantly, the members of the Council could determine the fate of the governor: William Farrar was on the Council when it elected [[John Pott]] as governor in 1628<ref name=Campbell1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/historyofcolonya00campuoft/page/182/mode/2up 182}} }} and he was on the Council <ref name=Brown1901/> when it arrested and temporarily deported Governor Harvey in 1635.<ref name=Bruce1894/><ref name=Tarter2017a/>\n\nIn August 1626, Farrar was also appointed by Yeardley as commissioner (i.e., [[magistrate#English common law tradition|magistrate]]) of the \"Upper Partes\"[sic]  which lies along the James River west of [[Flowerdew Hundred Plantation|Piersey's Hundred]] in the approximate area of [[Charles City County, Virginia|Charles City]] and [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico]] Counties today. Farrar was one of six commissioners appointed, however he was the one given the right of final judgement when present and allowed the discretion to hold monthly courts at either Jordan's Journey or [[Shirley Plantation|Shirley Hundred]].<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/106/mode/2up 106}} }}.  When Virginia became a crown colony, this appointment was renewed by the Governor [[John Harvey (Virginia)| Sir John Harvey]] in 1632<ref name=Hening1809/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/168 168}}}}\n\nAfter 1619, settlers could purchase the cost of transporting indentured servants from England to the new world as a contract that could redeemed as a headright, and these headright contracts could used for [[speculation]] by having them bought from, sold to, or traded with others.<ref name=Galenson1984/> William Farrar became involved in the sale of these contracts.<ref name=Southall1943/> For example, he is listed in patents as selling headrights to the settlers William Andrewes around 1628<ref name=Nugent1934/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/cavalierspioneer00nuge/page/13/mode/2up 13}} }} and Nathan Martin around 1636<ref name=Nugent1934/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/cavalierspioneer00nuge/page/41/mode/2up 41}} }}\n\n== Sale of inheritance ==\nWhen William Farrar's father, John the elder, died sometime before May 1628, he willed his various landholdings in Hertfordshire to William. In addition, John Farrar also stipulated that William and his family receive a \u00a320 annuity from his older brother from rents in Halifax Parish, Yorkshire and that William receive \u00a350 upon his return to England.<ref name= \"Farrer1936\"/> In 1631,  William Farrar returned to England to claim his inheritance.<ref name=McCartney2007/>  He then sold the assets from his inheritance to his brothers, including his annuity for \u00a3240 and his landholdings for \u00a3200, for a total of \u00a3440 (equivalent to about ${{formatnum:{{ To USD round|{{inflation|UK|440|1600}}|GBR|sf=3}}}} today)<ref name=Holmes1972/> and returned to Virginia.\n\n==Farrar's Island==\n[[File:Map of William Farrar&#039;s Patent for Farrar&#039;s Island and Environs.jpg|thumb|Approximate extent of William Farrar&#039;s 2000-acre land grant including Farrar&#039;s Island and environs as defined by 1637 patent]]\nAt the time of his death sometime before June 11, 1637, Farrar was described as being \"of Henrico\"<ref name=Nugent1934/>, one of eight [[shire|shires]] established in Virginia three years previously.<ref name=Hening1809/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/224 224}}}}  By the time of his death, he had established his headright to a 2000 acre land patent at a site that included [[Dutch Gap]] and the former settlement of [[Henricus|Henrico]]. This headright was given for 40 indentured servants, who were named in the patent.{{notetag|At least seven of the names of the patents were those of people listed as living with Farrar and Jordan in the Muster of 1624/1625,{{refn|name=Southall1943}}}} After Farrar's death, the headright was repatented to his oldest son,<ref name=McCartney2011/> his namesake who was twelve years old at the time, by John Harvey, who had returned from England and resumed his role as governor of the colony.<ref name= Tarter2017b/>\n\nThe patent was issued for land that included a peninsula formed by [[meander]] loop, or curl,<ref name = McJimsey1940/>}} of the James River subsequently known as [[Farrar's Island]]. It is described in the patent as abutting the [[glebe]] lands of [[Varina Farms|Varina]] in the east,{{notetag|The glebe of Varina's boundaries were mapped during an archaeological study performed just before the construction of the [[Varina-Enon Bridge]] at the glebe's former location.<ref name=Geier&McCartney2018/>}} and extending to the James River in the south, the end of the island (i.e., peninsula) in the west, and \"to the woods\" in the north.<ref name=Nugent1934/>  Farrar's Island remained with the Farrar family until it was sold in 1731.<ref name=Stanard1901/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notefoot}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Aughterson1998>{{cite book|editor=Aughterson, Kate|title=The English Renaissance: An Anthology of Sources and Documents|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uopDaWjyyekC&q=Westminster+#v=onepage&q=Westminster%2024%20August%201588&f=false|publisher=New York, NY: Routledge|year=1998|isbn=9780415271158|pp=201\u2013202}}</