 Sociological Chronicles|publisher=Institute of Public Administration|year=1999|isbn=1902448693|location=|pages=247\u2013259}}</ref> and led to the development of a clinical package of care now internationally known as \"active of management of labour\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=O'Driscoll|first1=K.|last2=Meagher|first2=D.|last3=Boylan|first3=P.|date=1996-03-21|title=A Clinical Trial of Active Management of Labor|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=334|issue=12|pages=797\u2013799|doi=10.1056/NEJM199603213341212|issn=0028-4793|pmid=8592558}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Neilson|first=J. P.|last2=Lavender|first2=T.|last3=Quenby|first3=S.|last4=Wray|first4=S.|date=2003-12-01|title=Obstructed labour - Reducing maternal death and disability during pregnancy|journal=British Medical Bulletin|language=en|volume=67|issue=1|pages=191\u2013204|doi=10.1093/bmb/ldg018|pmid=14711764|issn=0007-1420}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Myr|first=Rachel|date=2019-08-18|title=Reason for Active Management|url=https://www.bmj.com/rapid-response/2011/10/29/reason-active-management}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aims.org.uk/journal/item/active-management-of-labour|title=Active Management of Labour {{!}} AIMS|website=www.aims.org.uk|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> \n\nAfter his career at the National Maternity Hospital,  Meagher took over as Director General of the Holy Family Hospital in Bethlehem, in the West Bank. There, with the Order of Malta and the European Union, he helped build Palestine's first maternity ward, introduced maternity training programs for local doctors and midwives, and set up rural maternity care clinics for Palestinian women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/wren-boys-party-raises-funds-for-bethlehem-hospital-26025330.html|title=Wren Boys' party raises funds for Bethlehem hospital|website=independent|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.orderofmalta.int/humanitarian-medical-works/bethlehems-hospital/|title=Bethlehem's Hospital|website=Order of Malta|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> Meagher also represented Ireland on the council of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists in London, which he used to share maternity care practices and build ties between the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland. \n\nMeagher co-authored with  Kieran O'Driscoll, ''The Active Management of Labour'', which is used in medical school curricula in Europe, Australia, Canada, Great Britain, and the United States.<ref>{{Cite book|last=O'Driscoll, Kieran.|title=Active management of labour : the Dublin experience|date=2003|publisher=Mosby|others=Meagher, Declan., Robson, Michael.|isbn=978-0-7234-3202-9|edition=4th|location=Edinburgh|oclc=54966842}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/books/active-management-of-labour/odriscoll/978-0-7234-3202-9|title=Active Management of Labour - 4th Edition|website=www.elsevier.com|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meagher, Declan}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from County Offaly]]\n[[Category:Irish obstetricians]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declan_Meagher"}
{"title_page": "Mount Wilson (Vermont)", "text_new": "{{for|other uses of this name|Mount Wilson (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Mount Wilson\n| photo = \n| photo_caption = \n| map = Vermont\n| map_alt = Mount Wilson in the State of Vermont in the United States\n| map_caption = Vermont, U.S.A.\n| map_relief = yes\n| map_size = 200\n| elevation_ft = 3745\n| elevation_ref = <ref name=\"GMC Long Trail map\" />\n| prominence_ft = 200\n| prominence_ref = <ref name=\"peakbagger\" />\n| listing = {{pound}}92 [[New England Hundred Highest|New England 100 Highest]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| state = [[Vermont]]\n| district = [[Addison County, Vermont|Addison]]\n| district_type = County\n| city = [[Ripton, Vermont|Ripton]]\n| city_type = Town\n| range = [[Green Mountains]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|44|00|17|N|072|55|32|W |type:mountain_region:US-VT_scale:100000_source:GNIS|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=\"GNIS\" />\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] Lincoln Mountain Quad<ref name=\"USGS 1921\" />\n| type = \n| age = \n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = maintained hiking trail\n}}\n\n'''Mount Wilson''' is a mountain in the [[Green Mountains]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Vermont]]. Located in the [[Breadloaf Wilderness]] of the [[Green Mountain National Forest]], its summit is in the town of [[Ripton, Vermont|Ripton]] in [[Addison County, Vermont|Addison County]]. The mountain is named after [[Woodrow Wilson]], former president of the United States.<ref name=\"Bushnell 2019\" /> Flanked by [[Bread Loaf Mountain (Vermont)|Bread Loaf Mountain]] to the southwest, Mount Wilson is one of five peaks in Vermont's [[Presidential Range (Green Mountains)|Presidential Range]]. At {{convert|3745|feet}}, it is the 12th highest peak in Vermont and one of the hundred highest peaks in New England.\n\n==Drainage basin==\n\nMount Wilson stands within the [[drainage basin|watersheds]] of [[Lake Champlain]] and the [[Connecticut River]]. The southeast side of Mount Wilson drains into the [[headwaters]] of the [[White River (Connecticut River)|White River]], thence into the Connecticut River, which drains into [[Long Island Sound]] in [[Connecticut]]. The northeast side of Mount Wilson drains into the Clark Brook and thence into the White River. The northwest side of Mount Wilson drains into the headwaters of the [[New Haven River]], thence into [[Otter Creek (Vermont)|Otter Creek]], Lake Champlain, [[Canada]]'s [[Richelieu River]], the [[Saint Lawrence River]], and ultimately into the [[Gulf of Saint Lawrence]].\n\n==Hiking==\n\nThe [[Long Trail]] traverses the summit of Mount Wilson. Multiple side trails provide access to this section of the Long Trail. The Clark Brook Trail, whose trailhead is in the town of [[Granville, Vermont|Granville]], intersects the Long Trail after {{convert|3.0|mile|1}}. From the junction, Mount Wilson is {{convert|0.8|mile|1}} south on Long Trail. The Emily Proctor Trail, whose trailhead is in the town of [[Lincoln, Vermont|Lincoln]], terminates at the Emily Proctor Shelter after {{convert|3.5|mile|1}}. From the shelter, Mount Wilson is {{convert|0.9|mile|1}} north on Long Trail. In the opposite direction, Bread Loaf Mountain is {{convert|0.7|mile|1}} from the shelter.<ref name=\"GMC Long Trail map\" />\n\nThe Cooley Glen Trail, whose trailhead coincides with the Emily Proctor Trailhead, terminates at the Cooley Glen Shelter, which is approximately {{convert|4.8|mile}} north of Mount Wilson on the Long Trail. A popular loop hike begins and ends at the Emily Proctor Trailhead (or the Cooley Glen Trailhead in a clockwise direction). The {{convert|12.4|mile|adj=on|1}} loop hike takes in three peaks of the Presidential Range: Mount Wilson, [[Mount Roosevelt (Vermont)|Mount Roosevelt]], and [[Mount Cleveland (Vermont)|Mount Cleveland]]. A fourth president, [[Mount Grant (Vermont)|Mount Grant]], is just off the main loop, {{convert|0.8|mile|1}} north of the Cooley Glen Shelter on the Long Trail.<ref name=\"GMC Day Hiker\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of mountains in Vermont]]\n* [[List of New England Hundred Highest]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"GNIS\">{{cite gnis |id=1461622 |name=Mount Wilson |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"peakbagger\">{{cite peakbagger |pid=7024 |name=Mount Wilson, Vermont |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GMC Long Trail map\">{{cite map |author=[[Green Mountain Club]] |title=Vermont's Long Trail: A Footpath in the Wilderness |trans-title= |map= |map-url= |date= |year=2015 |url= |type=Topographic map |scale=1:85,000 |series= |publisher= |cartography=Center for Community GIS |page= |pages= |section= |sections= |inset= |edition=5th |location= |language= |format= |isbn=978-1-888021-46-2 |id= |ref= |access-date= |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GMC Day Hiker\">{{cite book |title=Day Hiker's Guide to Vermont |date=2011 |publisher=[[Green Mountain Club]] |location=Waterbury Center, Vermont |isbn=978-1-888021-35-6 |edition=6th}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Bushnell 2019\">{{cite web |last1=Bushnell |first1=Mark |title=Whence Camel's Hump and other Vermont mountain names? |url=https://vtdigger.org/2019/09/15/then-again-whence-camels-hump-and-other-vermont-mountain-names/ |publisher=[[VTDigger]] |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=September 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"USGS 1921\">{{cite web |title=USGS 1:62500-scale Quadrangle for Lincoln Mountain, VT 1921 |url=https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/usgs-1-62500-scale-quadrangle-for-lincoln-mountain-vt-1921 |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]] |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=1921}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Mountains of Vermont}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilson}}\n[[Category:Mountains of Vermont]]\n[[Category:New England Hundred Highest]]\n[[Category:Ripton, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Addison County, Vermont]]\n\n{{Vermont-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|other uses of this name|Mount Wilson (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Mount Wilson\n| photo = \n| photo_caption = \n| map = Vermont\n| map_alt = Mount Wilson in the State of Vermont in the United States\n| map_caption = Vermont, U.S.A.\n| map_relief = yes\n| map_size = 200\n| elevation_ft = 3745\n| elevation_ref = <ref name=\"GMC Long Trail map\" />\n| prominence_ft = 200\n| prominence_ref = <ref name=\"peakbagger\" />\n| listing = {{pound}}92 [[New England Hundred Highest|New England 100 Highest]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| state = [[Vermont]]\n| district = [[Addison County, Vermont|Addison]]\n| district_type = County\n| city = [[Ripton, Vermont|Ripton]]\n| city_type = Town\n| range = [[Green Mountains]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|44|00|17|N|072|55|32|W |type:mountain_region:US-VT_scale:100000_source:GNIS|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=\"GNIS\" />\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] Lincoln Mountain Quad<ref name=\"USGS 1921\" />\n| type = \n| age = \n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = maintained hiking trail\n}}\n\n'''Mount Wilson''' is a mountain in the [[Green Mountains]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Vermont]]. Located in the [[Breadloaf Wilderness]] of the [[Green Mountain National Forest]], its summit is in the town of [[Ripton, Vermont|Ripton]] in [[Addison County, Vermont|Addison County]]. The mountain is named after [[Woodrow Wilson]], former president of the United States.<ref name=\"Bushnell 2019\" /> Flanked by [[Bread Loaf Mountain (Vermont)|Bread Loaf Mountain]] to the southwest, Mount Wilson is one of five peaks in Vermont's [[Presidential Range (Green Mountains)|Presidential Range]]. At {{convert|3745|feet}}, it is the 12th highest peak in Vermont and one of the hundred highest peaks in New England.\n\n==Drainage basin==\n\nMount Wilson stands within the [[drainage basin|watersheds]] of [[Lake Champlain]] and the [[Connecticut River]]. The southeast side of Mount Wilson drains into the [[headwaters]] of the [[White River (Connecticut River)|White River]], thence into the Connecticut River, which drains into [[Long Island Sound]] in [[Connecticut]]. The northeast side of Mount Wilson drains into the Clark Brook and thence into the White River. The northwest side of Mount Wilson drains into the headwaters of the [[New Haven River]], thence into [[Otter Creek (Vermont)|Otter Creek]], Lake Champlain, [[Canada]]'s [[Richelieu River]], the [[Saint Lawrence River]], and ultimately into the [[Gulf of Saint Lawrence]].\n\n==Hiking==\n\nThe [[Long Trail]] traverses the summit of Mount Wilson. Multiple side trails provide access to this section of the Long Trail. The Clark Brook Trail, whose trailhead is in the town of [[Granville, Vermont|Granville]], intersects the Long Trail after {{convert|3.0|mile|1}}. From the junction, Mount Wilson is {{convert|0.8|mile|1}} south on Long Trail. The Emily Proctor Trail, whose trailhead is in the town of [[Lincoln, Vermont|Lincoln]], terminates at the Emily Proctor Shelter after {{convert|3.5|mile|1}}. From the shelter, Mount Wilson is {{convert|0.9|mile|1}} north on Long Trail. In the opposite direction, Bread Loaf Mountain is {{convert|0.7|mile|1}} from the shelter.<ref name=\"GMC Long Trail map\" />\n\nThe Cooley Glen Trail, whose trailhead coincides with the Emily Proctor Trailhead, terminates at the Cooley Glen Shelter, which is approximately {{convert|4.8|mile}} north of Mount Wilson on the Long Trail. A popular loop hike begins and ends at the Emily Proctor Trailhead (which coincides with the Cooley Glen Trailhead). The {{convert|12.4|mile|adj=on|1}} loop hike takes in three peaks of the Presidential Range: Mount Wilson, [[Mount Roosevelt (Vermont)|Mount Roosevelt]], and [[Mount Cleveland (Vermont)|Mount Cleveland]]. A fourth president, [[Mount Grant (Vermont)|Mount Grant]], is just off the main loop, {{convert|0.8|mile|1}} north of the Cooley Glen Shelter on the Long Trail.<ref name=\"GMC Day Hiker\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of mountains in Vermont]]\n* [[List of New England Hundred Highest]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"GNIS\">{{cite gnis |id=1461622 |name=Mount Wilson |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"peakbagger\">{{cite peakbagger |pid=7024 |name=Mount Wilson, Vermont |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GMC Long Trail map\">{{cite map |author=[[Green Mountain Club]] |title=Vermont's Long Trail: A Footpath in the Wilderness |trans-title= |map= |map-url= |date= |year=2015 |url= |type=Topographic map |scale=1:85,000 |series= |publisher= |cartography=Center for Community GIS |page= |pages= |section= |sections= |inset= |edition=5th |location= |language= |format= |isbn=978-1-888021-46-2 |id= |ref= |access-date= |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GMC Day Hiker\">{{cite book |title=Day Hiker's Guide to Vermont |date=2011 |publisher=[[Green Mountain Club]] |location=Waterbury Center, Vermont |isbn=978-1-888021-35-6 |edition=6th}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Bushnell 2019\">{{cite web |last1=Bushnell |first1=Mark |title=Whence Camel's Hump and other Vermont mountain names? |url=https://vtdigger.org/2019/09/15/then-again-whence-camels-hump-and-other-vermont-mountain-names/ |publisher=[[VTDigger]] |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=September 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"USGS 1921\">{{cite web |title=USGS 1:62500-scale Quadrangle for Lincoln Mountain, VT 1921 |url=https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/usgs-1-62500-scale-quadrangle-for-lincoln-mountain-vt-1921 |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]] |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=1921}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Mountains of Vermont}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilson}}\n[[Category:Mountains of Vermont]]\n[[Category:New England Hundred Highest]]\n[[Category:Ripton, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Addison County, Vermont]]\n\n{{Vermont-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Trscavo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHiking:minor edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w